<HEADLINE> Iraq Denounces US for Delaying Approval of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today announced the approval
of the detailed measures concerning Iraq's partial oil sale and
importation of humanitarian supplies by the U.N. Sanctions
Committee and denounced the hostile American attitude in delaying
the final endorsement.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) said that the approval of the
measures have been delayed by the United States for quite a number
of weeks and the American position toward the implementation of
the oil-for-food deal agreed by Iraq and the U.N. in May has drawn
 discontent from diplomats within and outside the Security Council
as well as criticism of world media.
</P>
<P>
INA said that 14 member states of the Security Council have
announced their agreement to the implementation of the
Iraq-U.N. oil deal. But the United States tried on purpose to
delay the approval of the details for the implementation of the
oil deal in an attempt to reach its goals, which are irrelevant to
the U.N. Charter and resolutions, it said.
</P>
<P>
Without American objection, Iraq could have started to export
in April a limited quantity of oil in exchange for badly needed
food, medicine and other humanitarian goods, the official news
agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Iraq held the United States fully responsible for aggravating
the sufferings of the Iraqi people under U.N. sanctions imposed
after it invaded Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq entered the dialogue with the U.N. to clinch the
oil-for-food deal in February. The deal allows Iraq to export oil
worth 2 billion U.S. dollars every six months to pay for food,
medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
With the final endorsement of the details for oil exporting,
Iraq's oil is expected to flow to the world market to help ease
the sufferings of its population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
