<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Urged to Stop Ground Subsidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Geologists warn that Shanghai,
China's largest city will be seriously affected if ground
subsidence, which is averaging 10 millimeters annually, is not
halted.
</P>
<P>
"The future existence and development of this city will be
endangered if we let ground subsidence continue uncontrolled,"
said Zhang Xianlin, director of the Shanghai City Geological
Research Institute, at the ongoing 30th International Geological
Congress in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said that the phenomenon is mainly the result of excessive
groundwater use and building construction. With a population of
some 13 million, the city's consumption of drinking water and that
used in industry has been on the rise over the past several
decades.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the 1955-65 period showed that the quantity of
groundwater drawn by the city was 200 million cubic meters
annually, causing the ground in urban districts to go down 1.75
meters on average.
</P>
<P>
Even though preventative measures have been taken, the quantity
of groundwater drawn by the city rose from 100 million cubic
meters in 1986 to 140 million cubic meters this year, and the
ground was subsiding 10 mm annually.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 high-rises built in Shanghai over the past ten years
have also contributed ot the ground subsidence, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has taken some preventative steps to
halt the subsidence, such as controlling the amount of groundwater
taken from the shallow layer, pouring water underground, and
drawing water from a deep stratum.
</P>
<P>
A monitoring network will be set up and a local regulation on
controlling ground subsidence is to be published in the near
future, Zhang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
