<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Health System in Crisis: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's health delivery system
is in a crisis and needs urgent reforms as the country exposes
itself to new ideas aimed at improving the economy, President
Robert Mugabe said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a medical conference to discuss Zimbabwe's health care
system, Mugabe said the recent dispute between doctors and
medical aid societies had shocked the country, with Zimbabweans
wondering whether they should expect health care providers to
behave differently from the purveyors of other goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe medical association and the national association
of medical aid societies have reached a stalemate on medical fees
to be charged to patients.
</P>
<P>
This has resulted in many doctors asking for cash from
patients who can claim from their medical aid societies.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, in Zimbabwe there is need for greater
complementarity between the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
He said the government could no longer shoulder the health
burden alone, hence there is need for alternative sources of
health care providers.
</P>
<P>
''It would appear to me that there is in our country today a
crisis in the provision of health services. Let me further
elaborate and say that we want more and better health care, but
to have such health care we need a system of paying for it that
distributes itself equitably and assures equal access for all the
citizens of our great country,'' Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, ''in the public sector, the government is
committed to care for the poor, the children and the elderly, and
yet the government cannot without limitation afford an ever
increasing financial burden, neither can the tax payer afford to
pick up the slack.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
