<HEADLINE> France Says Five Nuclear Powers Agree on Method of Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- France said today that the five
nuclear powers have agreed upon the method of on-site inspection
of nuclear installations suspected of violating the future
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
"In terms of this agreement by the five, an affirmative vote by
30 of the (51-member) executive committee of the future
organization will be necessary for authorizing the start of an
on-site inspection," said French Foreign Ministry vice-spokesman
Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
He said that France has played a "decisive role" in helping
bring about the agreement, but Paris does not think that all the
obstacles to the signing of CTBT has been removed.
</P>
<P>
The United States, France, Britain and Russia first proposed a
24-vote of simple majority out of 51 for authorizing such
inspections. China proposed 34, according to French diplomatic
sources.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that India is still blocking the
negotiations for the final adoption of the CTBT draft text by the
members of a U.N. ad hoc committee in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
India wants the draft text to include a calendar of nuclear
disarmament by the five nuclear powers, which has been rejected by
all the five.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the head of the Indian delegation Arundhati Ghose
has threatened not to sign the treaty. "We cannot let take away
our right of not to sign the treaty," she said.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign ministry spokesman said that it is the
sovereignty of India not to sign it, but "it is not in the interest
of India to block the transmission of the draft treaty to the U.N.
General Assembly."
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in Geneva expected the CTBT to be signed during the
next session of U.N. General Assembly from the end of September to
November in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
