<HEADLINE> Dialogue with Disabled on Hunger Strike Urged in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Senior leaders of Nepal's main
ruling party today urged the coalition government to talk with a
protesting disabled group on its welfare demands.
</P>
<P>
General Secretaries of the Nepali Congress (NC) Sushil Koirala
and Taranath Ranabhat, in their letters separately to Prime
Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba and Social Welfare Minister Lila
Koirala, called on the government to seek a solution to the
disabled's demands.
</P>
<P>
Six members of Nepal National Federation of the Disabled begun
a hunger strike here early this week to press the government to
meet the federation's 34-point demands which it handed over six
months ago.
</P>
<P>
The demands include better budgetary allocations, interest-free
loans, free health care, unemployment allowances and job training
for the disabled in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the Social Welfare Ministry Thursday issued a press
communique saying that an agreement had been reached earlier for
gradually meeting the group's demands following discussions
between ministry officials and representatives of the group.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, most of these demands, including
financial assistance, disabled allowances and scholarships for
disabled students, have been met and work regarding the
fulfillment of the other demands is underway.
</P>
<P>
But officials of the disabled federation said they want a
written agreement with the government on their demands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
