<HEADLINE> Jet Engine Inventor Frank Whittle Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Sir Frank Whittle, the inventor of
the jet engine, has died after a long battle against lung cancer
in the United States at the age of 89, Britain's Royal
Aeronautical Society announced here today.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Royal Aeronautical Society said this
afternoon "we can confirm that he has died at his home in
Maryland. He had been ill for some time."
</P>
<P>
Whittle, who was born in Coventry and joined the Royal Air
Force as an apprentice at 16, invented the jet engine in 1928 when
he was a young Royal Air Force cadet and two years later obtained
patent right for this revolutionary invention.
</P>
<P>
Jet fighters entered the World War II in 1944 and by 1949 Sir
Frank's design was in widespread use by Western air forces.
Britain's first plane fitted with a jet engine was the Gloster
E28/39 which made its first flight in May 1941.
</P>
<P>
Whittle is commonly regarded as standing among the great
pioneers of aviation history. Former British Airways chief Sir
Peter Masefield, who is a close friend of Whittle, described
Whittle as "a great man who changed the face of aviation."
</P>
</TEXT>
