<HEADLINE> SADC Protocol on Free Movement Shelved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 9 (Xinhua) -- SADC countries have failed to
agree on a draft protocol on the free movement of people in the
region and the matter has been dropped from the agenda of the
summit of SADC leaders scheduled for Maseru on August 24.
</P>
<P>
The SADC ministers responsible for home affairs and
immigration were expected to iron out outstanding issues on the
protocol at their June meeting in Botswana and present it to the
summit for signing.
</P>
<P>
However, some provisions in the draft were not immediately
acceptable to all the 12 member states of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
SADC Executive-Secretary Kaire Mbuende and Zimbabwean Home
Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa today told the Zimbabwe National
News Agency in separate interviews the protocol was definitely
not going to be discussed at this year's annual summit.
</P>
<P>
Particularly controversial was the proposed provision making
it a right for a national of any of the SADC countries to move
and settle in any country of his choice within the region.
</P>
<P>
Most of the countries are said to have felt that it should not
be a matter of right for a citizen of any country to settle in
another country, but that the move should be subject to other
considerations.
</P>
<P>
Dabengwa and Mbuende said they were confident the protocol
would be signed next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
