<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist Says Qinghai-Tibet Plateau Shift Related To Yunnan Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese geologist says the
continuing upward movement of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau caused the
earthquake in southwest China's Lijiang early this year that
killed at least 238 people.
</P>
<P>
The theory was put forth by Xiao Xuchang, a professor with the
Chinese Academy of Geological Sciences, at the 30th International
Geological Congress in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"The uplift of the plateau caused the accumulation of enormous
energy in the surrounding layer, and the eruption of the energy
brought about the earthquake," Xiao explained.
</P>
<P>
Located in northwestern Yunnan Province, on the eastern edge of
the plateau, 800-year-old Lijiang was devastated by the quake,
which measured seven on the Richter scale, on February 3 this
year. In addition to those killed, there were 3,800 seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
"We observed the changes in geological activity in the Lijiang
area when the quake took place," Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
Xiao and another geologist, Li Tingdong, have attracted
attention during the congress for publishing a new theory on the
plateau's swelling.
</P>
<P>
They say that the fast growth of the plateau, which has risen
about 10,000 meters in the past two million years, is resultant
from expansion of terrestrial heat and isostatic adjustment of the
plateau's crust. Qomolangma, or Mount Everest, rose 37 centimeters
during the past 30 years, according to Xiao.
</P>
<P>
The uplift has greatly affected the surrounding areas'
geological structures and climates, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
