<HEADLINE> Milosevic, Kornblum Meet on Upcoming Bosnian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic and visiting Assistant American State Secretary John
Kornblum held a meeting here today to discuss the upcoming
elections in Bosnia and other issues concerning regional peace.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the September elections would provide
for the most essential encouragement to the overall normalization
of situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Kornblum arrived here late Thursday from Sarajevo, where he
attended a meeting of the forum of the Muslim-Croat federation. He
will then travel to Zagreb after his visit to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of Kornblum's current tour is to lay the ground for
a meeting between President Milosevic, Croatian President Franjo
Tudjman and Bosnian Muslim leader Alija Izetbegovic in Geneva next
Wednesday which will be chaired by U.S. Secretary of State Warren
Christopher. Kornblum is also entrusted with preparing
Christopher's visit to the Balkan region next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, also attended by NATO Supreme Allied
Commander in Europe Gen. George Joulwan, both Milosevic and
Kornblum expressed their expectation that the elections would
enable a stepped-up return of refugees to their homes and
facilitate a process of restoration of confidence among Bosnian
citizens.
</P>
<P>
The two parties emphasized that it was of great importance to
hold the first post-war elections successfully by implementing the
Dayton agreement consistently and completely, Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the role of the NATO-led peace
Implementation Force (IFOR) and current questions regarding
relations between Yugoslavia and the United State. 
</P>
</TEXT>
