<HEADLINE> First National Children's Arts Festival in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 9 (Xinhua) -- A three-day Zimbabwe children's
arts festival featuring music, dance, drama and exhibitions
opened in Harare today.
</P>
<P>
The festival is the first of its kind involving child
performers and visual artists from all the country's 10
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Opening the festival, Sports, Recreation and Culture
Under-Secretary Charles Dzimba said the festival had managed to
transcend the artificial divide of former group a (mainly white)
and b schools (predominantly black).
</P>
<P>
Dzimba said it was pleasing to see Zimbabwean children break
socio-cultural barriers as Zimbabwean pupils and not as ethnic
groups, adding that it was from this cross-fertilization of ideas
and cultures that a truly Zimbabwean culture could be built.
</P>
<P>
''Zimbabwe is a multi-cultural, multi-racial society whose
primary objective should be to bring together all these different
cultures, synthesize them and come up with a Zimbabwean culture
that is both developmental and acceptable to all parties
regardless of social background,'' said Dzimba.
</P>
<P>
The festival seeks to help children discover aspects of their
own culture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
