<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Not Recommend a Return from Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- France is not recommending that its
citizens return from the central African state of Burundi as the
United States has done, French Foreign Ministry vice-spokesman
Yves Doutriaux said today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the number of French nationals in Burundi was not
high after the withdrawal of French military advisors from the
country in May, and the closing of a French school at Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said France did not want to comment on the
economic sanctions being imposed on Burundi by African countries
neighboring Burundi. But "one should follow very attentively the
effects of the sanctions on the humanitarian situation of the
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Burundi was completely isolated today after Rwanda decided to
close its borders to join the economic sanctions imposed by the
countries of the Great Lake region -- Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda and
Ethiopia. Burundi's border with Zaire has already been closed for
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
However, Rwandan Hutu refugees continued to pour into Rwanda
from Burundi today despite the closure of the border, said
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Some 8,600 Rwandan Hutu refugees returned to Rwanda on Thursday
after 8,450 others crossed the border on Wednesday, Agence France
Presse quoted United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR)
officials as saying in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR officials said the number of refugees expected to
cross the border today would not be less than Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 Rwandan Hutu refugees are living in northern
Burundi. They fled Rwanda in fear of reprisals by the
Tutsi-dominated National Patriotic Front after the genocide in
Rwanda in the summer of 1994, which killed at least half a million
Tutsis and Hutu moderates.
</P>
<P>
Burundi's Tutsi-dominated military staged a putsch late last
month ousting a Hutu president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
