<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No U.S. Deaths Are Attributed To Cow Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 9 (Xinhua) -- No evidence indicated that
anyone in the U.S. has died of the Creutzdeldt-Jakob (C-J)disease
which is on a likely link with "mad cow", according to the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
British scientists reported in March about 10 cases of C-J
diseases that could be attributed to bovine spongiform
encephalopathy. Scientists with the Federal agency then began
surveying doctors and pathologists in five states to determine
whether there was any evidence of the variant in this country.
</P>
<P>
The agency also began reviewing death certificates to determine
whether there had been any increase in C-J disease, particularly
among people under 30 years old. From 1990 to 1994, the disease
was listed as a cause of death for only two people under 30 and no
link to mad cow was found.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey about 800 neurologists and
neuropathologists in Connecticut, Minnesota, Oregon, the San
Francisco Bay area and Atlanta, only 94 deaths were caused by C-J
disease and no one was attributed to "mad cow" disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
