<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-09 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus President to Monitor Motorcycle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
and Defense Minister Costas Eliades will monitor the final stage
of Sunday's anti-Turkish occupation motorcycle demonstrations at
police headquarters in Nicosia, Cyprus News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Their presence comes amid serious concern over the event, which
the Cyprus government and the U.N. are afraid of causing riots in
the 180-kilometer-long buffer zone, which divides the island into
two parts, the Greek Cypriot south and the Turkish Cypriot north.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Justice and Public Order Minister Alecos Evangelou will
also be in the police operations room to monitor the ride, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
About 120 bikers started a 10-day ride from Berlin last Friday
and will arrive at Limassol port here Saturday morning aboard a
ship from Greece.
</P>
<P>
The following day they will be joined by about 7,000 Greek
Cypriot bikers, and together they will stage a ride along the
buffer zone, and will attempt to ride to northern coastal town of
Kyrenia.
</P>
<P>
Both the Cyprus government and the U.N. have warned against
trouble in the buffer zone during the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot press reported that the Turkish troops had
been ordered to shoot anyone who attempts to cross into the
Turkish-controlled northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Police chief Panikos Hadjiloizou, however, said that police
will use all available means to avert any incidents on the
motorcycle demonstration and to ensure the status of the
U.N.-controlled buffer zone is not violated.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and seized the northern third of the island following an
Athens-backed coup.
</P>
<P>
The 1,200-strong U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP)
has been patrolling along the 180-kilometer-long buffer zone
separating the Turkish troops from the Greek Cypriot National
Guards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
