<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Test Ban Talks Still Hang in Balance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The prospect of the Geneva-based
Conference on Disarmament adopting the comprehensive nuclear test
ban treaty by consensus still remains unclear as India continues
to threaten blockage such agreement.
</P>
<P>
Asked after a negotiators' meeting on Friday if India would
block the treaty, Indian Ambassador Arundhati Ghose reiterated her
earlier position: "If they don't change the Entry-Into-Force
clause, we'll have to."
</P>
<P>
However, it is unlikely that the treaty text could still be
opened up for further changes to the Entry-Into-Force issue, says
Dutch Ambassador Jaap Ramaker, who chairs the test ban talks.
</P>
<P>
But Ghose told reporters that she was hopeful that changes
would occur. "We're still talking", she said.
</P>
<P>
According to Indian officials' statements earlier, India
opposes the Entry-Into-Force clause of the current draft treaty
because it includes wording that could lead to UN Security Council
sanctions against India if it refuses to ratify the treaty, an
interpretation with which Ramaker disagreed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some diplomats here believe that India is just holding out to
press for some sort of assurances from other countries that no
sanctions will be imposed if the country does refuse to ratify the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier that Washington and its allies had
devised a legal stratagem to sidestep India's veto -- a group of
states might be able to present the treaty directly to the UN
General Assembly without a specific endorsement by the disarmament
Conference.
</P>
<P>
But some countries fear such a move could undermine the
credibility of the Conference, which always operates by consensus,
and could set an undesirable precedent for future disarmament
negotiations under the Conference.
</P>
<P>
Iran also expressed the view that the current draft treaty
should not list Israel as one of the members of the treaty's
executive council representing Middle East and South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Ramaker also proposed a modification to the current
draft treaty on the subject of on-site inspections.
</P>
<P>
Under this, international inspections at the site of suspected
treaty violations would go forward only when at least 30 of the 51
nations in the treaty's executive council agreed, rather than by
the simple majority vote suggested by the current draft treaty.
</P>
<P>
The "30" formula was believed to be the outcome of a deal last
week between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said that Ramaker was expected to submit a final
report to the Conference on Disarmament early next week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
