<HEADLINE> S. Africa Marks National Women's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Over 20,000 local women in
their traditional dresses, joined by a colorful band, marched
through the streets of South Africa's capital of Pretoria to
celebrate the national women's day.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the gathering, President Nelson Mandela said
a new democratic South Africa has marked out significant
milestones toward improving the status of women.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also praised women's role in making South Africa's
history, vowed to free them from the suffering of poverty, and
promised to work for the equity of women.
</P>
<P>
The president made references to the 124 women delegates in
the 490-member parliament, four women cabinet ministers and eight
deputy ministers, five women ambassadors and 15 chairwomen of
parliamentary committee.
</P>
<P>
"That is a small beginning, but we have made a start. Our aim
is to have half the members of cabinet women," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The gathering was joined by African National Congress Women's
League President Winnie Mandela and Deputy-President Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
