<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Makes Up Mind on Running Mate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 9 (Xinhua)-- U.S. Republican presidential
challenger Bob Dole said this morning that he had decided on a
running mate in the November 5 elections, but gave no clue as to
who would share the GOP ticket.
</P>
<P>
Dole, talking to reporters aboard his campaign plane en route
to kansas, said only that the person would be "probably an 11" on
a scale of 1 to 10. Tax-cut champion and former U.S. Housing
Secretary Jack Kemp was widely believed as the top contender,
followed by Florida Sen. Connie Mack.
</P>
<P>
Dole said he would probably notify his intended choice this
evening, and proceed with plans to formally unveil his running
mate on Saturday in his hometown of Russell, Kansas.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. Senate Majority Leader has repeatedly noted
that the choice of the running mate is the most important decision
in his campaign. Dole had twice failed to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Campaign sources said that Kemp, an energetic campaigner who
has had prickly relations with Dole over the years, had informed
Dole's campaign chief Scott Reed that he would accept the job if it
were offered him.
</P>
<P>
Kemp emerged as a prospect in recent days as Dole and top
advisers looked beyond their existing list for a candidate who
would generate enthusiasm at next week's Republican National
Convention in San Diego and be attractive to independent voters
critical to Dole's chances of erasing President Clinton's healthy
lead. Recent polls show that Dole lags behind Clinton by as many
as 20 points.
</P>
<P>
Kemp is a leader of Empower America, a conservative policy
organization whose leaders also include William Bennett, the
former Education secretary and drug czar.
</P>
<P>
In addition to his work at Empower America, he has made a
healthy living by delivering paid speeches and serving on several
corporate boards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0037 </DOCNO>
