<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea, Japan Fail to Revise Fishery Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan concluded
their two-day fishery talks here today, but failed to narrow
differences over whether the coastal state principle, which allows
coastal states to apprehend ships of any country operating
illegally in their waters, should be introduced.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the second of its kind, South Korea put
forward three major principles which include the establishment of
a new fishing order in Northeast Asia, respect for existing
fishing patterns and impartiality in setting price standards and
the amount of fish caught and consideration of the special
historical relationship between the two countries in connection
with the fishing treaty.
</P>
<P>
Japan, meanwhile, proposed that the two sides come up with a
new fishery pact which guarantees the coastal state principle and
introduces a total allowable catch system, under which ships can
operate in waters of other countries on the condition that they
pay the necessary fees and catch only what their quota allows.
</P>
<P>
Lee Won-hyung, deputy director-general of the Asia-Pacific
Affairs Bureau of the South Korean Foreign Ministry, said after
the talks that the Seoul-Tokyo fishery talks should procced in
harmony with the talks for setting the boundaries of the Exclusive
Economic Zone (EEZ) of the two countries, adding that the fishery
zones cannot be separated from the EEZs.
</P>
<P>
"In that sense, the talks on fishery pact and the demarcation
of EEZs, now under way in separate talks, will have to get
together at some point in the future," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea and Japan will hold talks in Tokyo on August 13 to
discuss the EEZ demarcations for the two countries under the
United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea.
</P>
<P>
Lee expected that the talks on fishery pact revisions and EEZ
demarcations will last up to two years, considering the
complicated matters involved, although Japan wants to conclude
them as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
