<HEADLINE> Ex-Chief of Elf Accused of Organized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- A magistrate of a court of Paris
has accused former president of the Elf-Aquitaine oil group Loik
Le Floch-Prigent of "organized diversion" of public fund during
his term as head of the largest industrial enterprise of France
from 1989 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the local daily Le Monde for its
Saturday-Sunday edition, Judge Eva Joly is to summon Prigent for a
new hearing today.
</P>
<P>
Le Floch-Prigent has been detained since July 4 for suspected
abuse of public fund, abuse of confidence and covering of these
acts. He was president of the National Railway Company of France
when arrested.
</P>
<P>
In an ordinance signed by Joly for his detention, Prigent is
accused of "pursuing the aim of enriching his family members and
friends" and taking advantage of the financial structure of Elf
as "tools for organized diversion" of public fund in the file of
Elf.
</P>
<P>
When Prigent was president of Elf, 736 million francs (147
million U.S. dollars) was injected in a zigzag way into
ready-to-wear companies belonging to the Maurice Bidermann group.
</P>
<P>
Some 163 million francs was offered by the Elf-Gabon branch to
Bidermann for real estate operations, in which the ex-wife of
Prigent was suspected of having obtained a department in London as
part of condition for settling her divorce with Prigent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two key players in the financial scandal are now
hiding abroad and have refused to return to France to attend court
hearings.
</P>
<P>
Alfred Sirven, former director of general affairs of Elf and
personal advisor of Prigent, is staying in Switzerland with a
Swiss residential card.
</P>
<P>
Attorney Claude Richard, who is suspected to be the arranger of
several "financial montage" between Elf and Bidermann, is now
hiding in Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
