<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Justice Minister Sevket
Kazan today questioned the Western countries' criticism and
accusations against Turkey's human rights, saying they are biased
against Turkey on the issue.
</P>
<P>
His comments came after western countries strongly criticized
the Turkish government for the recent "death fast" in Turkish
prisons which resulted in 12 deaths.
</P>
<P>
The hunger strikes ended in late July following the mediation
efforts by some Turkish intellectuals and representatives of the
pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP).
</P>
<P>
"The West only deals with a specific group of people in
Turkey, but they are indifferent to the really unfair and unjust
issues in this country," said the minister without specifying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government was responding constructively to
some of the Western criticisms, adding that "Of course, we are
not completely indifferent to the comments of the West."
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 leftist inmates launched the hunger strike in May to
protest harsh inmate transfers, inadequate medical care and
restrictions on visitation rights for political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The hunger-strikers ended their strike after the government
agreed to let prisoners stay in the same city where they are on
trial. 
