<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Cabinet Approves Amended Election Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Council of Ministers,
in an extraordinary session presided by President Elias Hrawi
tonight, endorsed a revised bill on election just one day after
the previous law was overruled by the Constitutional Council.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet approved the amendment of the election law "at a
supersonic speed" in an attempt to avoid a postponement of the
upcoming parliamentary election, which is scheduled to start on
August 18, diplomatic sources in the Lebanese capital said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the cabinet session held in the Beirut
Presidential Palace, Minister of Agriculture Shawki Fakhoury
announced that the bill, which the Council of Ministers approved
tonight, was identical with the decision of the Constitutional
Council.
</P>
<P>
Fakhoury told reporters that the bill would be immediately
handed over to the parliament after the unicameral house took a
decision earlier today to open an extraordinary general session
next week to discuss the bill.
</P>
<P>
He added that the president, at the beginning of the meeting,
expressed his "complete respect" for the verdict issued by the
Constitutional Council in its capacity as the independent supreme
authority.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister declined to disclose the contents of the
amendment before it was put in front of the members of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Ruling out a postponement of the parliamentary election, which
was commonly expected by the Beirut media after the Thursday rule
of the Constitutional Council against the controversial election
law, Fakhouri stressed that "the schedule of the election remains
what it was."
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Hrawi, House Speaker Nabih Berri and Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri held an urgent meeting earlier today to
consider the Constitutional Council's verdict.
</P>
<P>
In the verdict published by the local newspapers this morning,
the 10-member court said it has unanimously annulled an article
dividing the country into 10 constituencies, six in Mount Lebanon
and four in other areas.
</P>
<P>
The verdict also cancelled an article banning civil servants
from returning to their jobs if they run the election and fail,
and another extending the next parliament's four-year term by
eight months.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parliamentary members, who lodged the petition
to the court, argued that the law passed by the parliament on July
11 discriminated the Lebanese voters by using dual standards in
dividing the constituencies.
</P>
<P>
"The law, in its second article, discriminates in treatment
among citizens, candidates and voters, in rights and duties,
without stating that this is on an exceptional basis called for
by special circumstances," the Constitutional Council said in the
ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
