<HEADLINE> Nigerian Researchers Find New Cereal Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's National Institute of
Horticultural Research and Training (NIHORT) said today that it
has discovered another source of cereal food with high protein.
</P>
<P>
According to NIHORT Acting Director Williams Eguage, research
embarked upon at the institute since 1984 has shown that the
seeds of grain amaranth, the biological name for the Nigerian
vegetable (spinach) commonly called "green" in local market,
contain 100 percent protein.
</P>
<P>
The mature seed can be processed into flour for staple food
like amala, pap, cake and bread with high concentration of
protein, carbohydrate and fat, Eguage said.
</P>
<P>
This quality made the grain amaranth cereal a complete and
better digestable food than most other foods, he added. 
</P>
