<HEADLINE> Bank of Canada Cuts Rates Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Canada today cut its
key overnight rate by a quarter of a percentage point to prod the
sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth time this year that the central bank lowered
its key interest rates. The last rate cut was made just three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The key rate is now in an operating band of 4.0 to 4.50
percent.
</P>
<P>
Following the bank's rate cut, the Bank of Montreal, Scotiabank
and other commercial banks announced they will cut their prime
lending rates to 6.00 percent from 6.25 percent, effective on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Statistics Canada reported that the national
unemployment rate edged down 0.2 percent to 9.8 percent in July
from 10 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The economy added 19,000 jobs, partly offsetting a decline of
56,000 in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the report, the Bank of Canada made the rate
cut, which has reinforced the message that it wants the economy to
pick up the pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
