<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blindness Drops by Thirty-five Percent in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' blindness
prevalence has dropped by 35 percent in eight years, the
Department of Health said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a 1995 national survey released by the department,
the prevalence of blindness dropped to 0.7 percent of the
population last year from 1.07 percent in 1987.
</P>
<P>
If the trend continues, the government can attain the 0.5
percent goal set by the World Health Organization by the year
2000, said the department.
</P>
<P>
The survey also reveals that the cataract operation backlog in
the country fell by 34 percent, from 558,000 in 1987 to 368,000 in
1995.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that by the year 2040, a zero cataract backlog
can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Carmencita Reodica said the Health Department
is currently cooperating with Helen Keller International to train
rural physicians as ophthalmologists in efforts to achieve a more
even distribution of eye specialists in the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
