<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Active Volcano Forces Evacuation of Villagers in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of villagers living in
border areas of central Java and Yogjakarta, 1,200 kilometers east
of Jakarta, were evacuated to safer areas after Merapi Mountain
showed its rising activities Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"More clouds which were spewed from Mount Merapi show that the
volcano has an increasing activity," Antara news agency quoted the
spokesman for the local volcanology office, Atje Purbawinata, as
saying today.
</P>
<P>
"Today the volcano has spewed hot clouds 23 times only in five
hours," he said, adding that the dangerous situation had caused
evacuation of people living in Boyong and Krasak rivers.
</P>
<P>
The Merapi volcano is classified by volcanologists as an
"explosive" type, similar to the volcano which devastated the
Caribbean island of Martinique at the turn of the century, leaving
29,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
Merapi rises to a height of 2,962 meters. To the east it
overlooks the most famous Indonesian monument, the Buddhist temple
of Borobodur, and 30 kilometers to the south the university city
of Yogjakarta, where one million people live.
</P>
<P>
Around 50,000 people live in the immediate vicinity of the
volcano, one of 127 active volcanoes out of 500 cataloged in the
Indonesian archipelago.
</P>
<P>
The region is a geologically unstable area which makes up part
of the Pacific "Ring of Fire."  
</P>
</TEXT>
