<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholars Call for Reform of Chinese Teaching in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Language experts from Hong Kong
have called for an overall reform of teaching methods of Chinese
language in order to help HK residents learn to speak standard
Chinese as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
They say that although more people in Hong Kong feel the
urgency of learning standard Chinese, schools in HK generally lack
both textbooks and teachers in that area.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came at the Fifth International Symposium on
Teaching Chinese as A Foreign Language, which opened in Huairou
County outside Beijing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Putonghua", or standard Chinese pronunciation, should be used
for upper-level courses in order to arouse patriotism among HK's
young, suggested Winnie Y.W. Auyeung Lai, director of the Hong
Kong Putonghua Education and Assessment Center.
</P>
<P>
Students should have a greater chance to study and to practice
speaking putonghua, said Leung Chung Sun from Hong Kong University.
</P>
<P>
Most people in Hong Kong speak Guangdong dialect (Cantonese)
and English, he noted, adding that students in schools have few
chances to speak putonghua.
</P>
<P>
"Such a situation is detrimental to exchanges between Hong Kong
and other parts of China and will also weak Hong Kong
competitiveness in the world," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
"Students in Hong Kong should also learn the simplified Chinese
characters," said Suen Caesar Lun, an assistant professor at Hong
Kong University. He has developed a computer software to help HK
people learn simplified characters and intends to introduced it to
local middle schools this year.
</P>
<P>
A course in putonghua will be given to primary and
middle-school students starting in September, 1998, and it will be
part of middle-school students' graduation exams by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Education Department of Hong Kong is drawing up a new
outline for putonghua teaching.
</P>
<P>
The symposium highlighted the role of teaching Chinese as a
foreign language in spreading the influence of Chinese culture in
the world, attracting some 40 experts from Hong Kong, Macao,
Taiwan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
