<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 10 -- The following are business briefs from
the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has decided to lower charges for handling goods
at the Red-Sea port of Aqaba, the English-language daily Jordan
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Captain Mohammad Dlabeeh, the new director-general of the
Ports Corporation, was quoted as saying that the reductions in
service charges approved recently by the cabinet would lower the
overall cost for each 20-feet container to nearly 66 dinars (about
92.4 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Handling expenses were lowered by 20 percent and loading and
unloading charges by 25 percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
As to vegetables and fruits, charges were reduced by 42
percent while the reduction for frozen food was 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Arab oil producers have slashed their
current deficit by more than a quarter in 1995 as they pressed
ahead with reforms and earned more from oil exports, an official
report from the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting
Countries said.
</P>
<P>
The report said the combined deficit in the current accounts
of the organization's countries dropped to 9.38 billion
U.S. dollars in 1995 from 13.72 billion dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 gap is nearly 20 percent of the record deficit of 46.4
billion dollars in 1991, when more than 60 billion
dollars were siphoned out of the state treasury in Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait to finance the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan exported 37.8 tons of fruit and vegetables
estimated at 5.95 million dinars (about 8.33 million dollars) in
July, compared with 29.64 tons during the same period last month.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An international conference on GATT impact on
Egyptian textile and ready-to-wear clothes sectors will be held in
Cairo in October, according to today's Arabic-language newspaper
Akhbar Al-Yom.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted General Director of the Egyptian Textile
Industries Chamber Shehata Semeda as saying that the International
Trade Council in Geneva, in cooperation with Egypt's Chamber
Textile of Industries and Commercial Representation Authority,
will organize this conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference will discuss the impact of removing quotas on
international textile trade and GATT impact on Egypt's trade
volume of ready-to-wear clothes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
