<HEADLINE> Egypt Sees Israel's Settlement Policy Harmful to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said today that Israel's
decision to resume expansion of Jewish settlements in the
Palestinian territories will have an adverse impact on the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters that this
Egyptian stand on Israel's settlement policy is clear, and the
Palestinians, the Arab world and the international community also
hold such a stand.
</P>
<P>
"The settlement policy is a grave danger to peace and stability
in the region and the whole peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa made the remarks following a meeting between Mubarak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who arrived here earlier today
on a brief visit.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet voted unanimously last Friday to lift the
building restrictions on construction in the Jewish settlements in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The restrictions were imposed by Israel's late Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin four years ago to pave the way for peace
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
On Israel's demand for the closure of the PLO offices in
Jerusalem, Moussa said the demand can not be accepted or dealt
with positively.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that all agreements, including the Oslo accords,
must be implemented, and that any measures that impede progress
in Palestinian-Israeli talks must be avoided.
</P>
<P>
Israel demanded Friday that the PLO halt activity in Arab East
Jerusalem before any peace talks could resume.
</P>
<P>
At their talks, Moussa said, Mubarak and Arafat expressed
concern over Israel's settlement policy and the Jerusalem issue.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to continue their meetings to coordinate
their stances on the peace process, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been playing an active role in the peace process as a
mediator between Israel and the Arabs, particularly the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has frequently visited Egypt for consultations with
Mubarak on the developments of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting came as the latest of a flurry of contacts held
between Arab leaders to revive the Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
It was the third summit Mubarak has held with Arab leaders
since his return from a U.S. visit earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak met with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad Wednesday and
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia Thursday to explore ways to resume peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Cairo, Arafat will chair a Fatah Central
Committee meeting to discuss the recent developments related to
peace talks with Israel and the situation in the Palestinian
self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
