<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen On Hong Kong Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
described forming the Selection Committee for the establishment of
the first goverment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) as "an historical event for Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
It shows that the majority of the people of Hong Kong will
begin to become their own masters politically, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is also the first time for the Hong Kong people to truly
and democratically participate in government and political affairs
on such a large scale," he added.
</P>
<P>
In the closing speech at the fourth plenary session of the
Preparatory Committee of SAR here today, Qian, who is chairman of
the committee, said that Britain has had more than 20 governors of
Hong Kong in the past century, but has never consulted the people
there.
</P>
<P>
"To form an organ to choose the chief executive and legislature
by the Hong Kong people themselves was really inconceivable under
colonial rule," he pointed out, while refuting allegation of
"democratic termination of Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, after Hong Kong returns to the motherland, it
will be the start of Hong Kong's true democracy by implementing
participation in government and political affairs by Hong Kong
people," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
On forming the Selection Committee, Qian said the principle of
"Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" must be the case, and that
the Selection Committee is definitely a unit with the people who
love the motherland and Hong Kong as the mainstay.
</P>
<P>
It should be represented as broadly as possible, with people
from various fields, social circles, and types of business, he
added.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that in forming the Selection Committee
non-Chinese permanent residents who have made a contribution to
Hong Kong are also welcome, as Hong Kong's status as an
international commercial metropolis should be reflected.
</P>
<P>
There are also people in Hong Kong, who are in favor of Hong
Kong's returning to China but have different views on the path and
pace of democratic development in Hong Kong, Qian noted.
</P>
<P>
However, if there is basis of supporting China's sovereignty
over Hong Kong and Hong Kong's stable transition, prosperity and
stability, people should and can sit together and discuss Hong
Kong's affairs, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
