<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reins in Major Geological Hazards (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- China has scored some successes
in recent years in controlling major geological hazards that posed
a serious threat to highways and residential areas, such as rock
or landslides, mud flows, and ground subsidence, according the
Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, China held back a landslide at Jipazi in southwest
China's Sichuan Province, protecting navigation on the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, geological departments successfully forecast a
landslide at Xintan, in Hubei Province in central China, and
evacuated 1,317 people in time, with no casualties as a result.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, predicting a landslide helped 488 people in Zhongyang
Village in Sichuan avoid a disaster.
</P>
<P>
With its complex geology, China has many kinds of hazards,
which cost the country billions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1981, the ministry has done studies in Sichuan, Yunnan,
Anhui, Jiangsu, Hebei, Shaanxi, Gansu and other provinces or
autonomous regions that are seriously plagued by geological
hazards, and have marked danger areas where people should be
careful.
</P>
<P>
China has started to control major geological hazards that may
cause casualties or economic losses. A special fund set aside by
the government has supported a survey of 72 geological hazards,
such as karst cave-ins at Tangshan City, ground subsidence at
Tianjin municipality, and rock falls in Chongqing City.
</P>
<P>
The special fund has also been allocated and used to control
landslides or mud flows in Sichuan Province's Douyapeng and
Hanyuan counties and Yunnan Province's Dongchuan City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Controls Major Geological Hazards (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ministry has made strenuous efforts to deal with the
threats at Lianziya and Huanglashi in the area of the Three Gorges
on the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Lianziya (Chain Cliff), a rock mass that is 2.5 million cubic
meters in size, and Huanglashi, a potential landslide that is 18
million cubic meters in size, pose a serious threat to navigation
on the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has projects for controlling the two hazards being
done by teams of engineering. The first phase of the Lianziya
project has been finished, while work on controlling Huanglashi is
in full swing. Both projects are expected to be completed this
year.
</P>
<P>
China has also been successful in preventing the ground around
Shanghai, the largest industrial city in the country, from further
sinking. Efforts have been made to control the excessive tapping
of groundwater by pumping water back into the ground and adjusting
the layers that are used.
</P>
<P>
At present, the sinking in Shanghai has almost been stopped,
and sinking in another major city, Tianjin, has also decreased
dramatically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
