<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Isolates Cholera-hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia today isolated two
major northern cities and some other areas in a bid to halt the
spread of cholera which has killed six people and infected 39
others in recent days.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the outbreak started in remote Khoetol county in
northern Selenge province which borders Russia. The disease
claimed two lives and infected 31 others in the county. Two of
them are in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The disease spread to the provincial capital, Darhan, the
country's second largest city. Two people, who had earlier left
Khoetol county before the region was isolated, died there,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said at least seven people had been diagnosed as infected
by the cholera in Darhan, which is about 350 kilometers north of
the Mongolian capital of Ulan Bator. Four of them were in a
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The government on Friday ordered civil defence troops to
quarantine Darhan, Khoetol county, some other areas of Selenge
province and the city of Erdenet, capital of a neighboring
province.
</P>
<P>
To protect the capital from the cholera, all rail connections
had been cut between Ulan Bator and Darhan, and with Erdenet,
local television reports said.
</P>
<P>
Police in Ulan Bator had been alerted to be ready to limit
travel in and out of the city at any time, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
A temporary ban was declared today (Saturday) on weekend
picnickers crossing the capital's borders. Water supply sources
for Ulan Bator were placed under tight police control, a police
officer said.
</P>
<P>
An emergency committee was formed today by the Health Ministry
to combat the disease.
</P>
<P>
Health officials said the cholera had probably been spread by
contaminated food and warned the public not to drink unboiled
water.
</P>
<P>
In another development today, civil defense officials said
flash floods in the suburbs of Ulan Bator had killed six people
since Thursday, bringing the death toll from floods in recent
weeks to 24.
</P>
<P>
The floods followed rainstorms late on Thursday which destroyed
roads and dozens of felt tents in districts to the northwest of
the capital, the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
