<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Desertification Document Passed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- A document that was passed here
today by 23 Asian and African countries is expected to help
efforts to combat desertification that plagues much of Asia and
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Framework for Action on Asia-Africa Co-operation on
Combating Desertification and/or Mitigating the Effects of
Droughts was passed at an Asia-Africa forum on the topic.
</P>
<P>
The framework suggests actions for combating desertification in
the 23 countries.
</P>
<P>
The forum was sponsored by the United Nations, Japan, and China
and was held from August 5-10. It also called for the secretariat
of the United Nations Convention on Combating Desertification
(CCD) to set up a department of Asian and African affairs, and
regional offices in Asia and Africa to help them develop
technology and seek assistance.
</P>
<P>
According to the CCD secretariat, desertification in Asia
amounts to 1.4 billion hectares and one billion ha in Africa. The
combined desertified land in the two continents accounts for
one-third of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
According to the framework, four priorities include attempting
to eliminate poverty through improving and optimizing different
ecological systems and integrated development of different kinds
of energy, slowing soil degradation through soil conservancy, and
water resources management and afforestation.
</P>
<P>
The other areas of action are construction of a data bank on
combating desertification and drought, information and monitoring
systems, and cooperation in finding effective ways to combat
desertification through laws, setting up organizations, and
exchanges on natural resources management.
</P>
<P>
The forum also developed a nine-point proposal to expand
cooperation and exchanges between Asian and African countries in
combating desertification, such as establishing a
desertification-control demonstration in two specific countries
and setting up a desertification research and technical training
center.
</P>
<P>
The CCD was signed by about 100 countries in 1994, the first
international convention following the United Nations Environment
and Development Summit Meeting held in Brazil in 1992.
</P>
<P>
One billion people in about 100 countries have been threatened
by desertification or drought, including 400 million of China's
1.2 billion people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf War Causes Extensive Damage to Kuwaiti Desert: Geologist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Farouk el-Baz, director of the
Center for Remote Sensing at Boston University, said today that
the 1991 Gulf War did damage to some 30 percent of Kuwait's
deserts.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, the Egyptian-American geologist
who has been here attending the 30th International Geological
Congress, said that he came to the conclusion after two and half
years of research on the impact of the war on the desert.
</P>
<P>
The project was sponsored by the Kuwait Foundation for the
Advancement of Science. Baz made 12 field trips to Kuwait where he
saw the great damage to the environment, and he has called for the
reduction of war and protection of the environment.
</P>
<P>
During the war, he said, the two sides used tens of thousands
of tanks and other heavy military vehicles, and a study of
satellite photos along with the field studies showed that military
vehicles destroyed small rocks that protect the sand and soil from
wind erosion, resulting in the formation of many new sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
Mine-sweeping after the war also caused the removal of the
desert pavement.
</P>
<P>
He said that the digging of trenches and building of bermes to
hide military personnel and hardware also exposed the sand, and
the exposure of fine-grained soil, combined with the action of the
prevailing northwesternly wind, moved vast amounts of dust and
sand.
</P>
<P>
The geologist explained that the number of sandstorms in
Kuwait, most of whose territory is desert, is now double the
figure before 1991 and that they often cover roads, farmland, and
the airport.
</P>
<P>
He said the second impact comes from the formation of 240 oil
lakes and two large strips of 12 cm thick hardened layer caused by
oil droplets and soot from the fires from 730 oil wells.
</P>
<P>
The geologist explained that the soil in the strips and the oil
lakes was poisoned, resulting in the destruction of natural
vegetation.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, it is possible that poisonous elements from the
oil may seep downward to pollute underground water.
</P>
<P>
The 58-year-old scientist, who participated in the Apollo
Program from 1967 to 1972 as a supervisor of lunar science
planning and of lunar exploration and the US-USSR joint Lunar
Cartographic Programs, coordinated the first visit by
U.S. scientists to the deserts in northwest China in 1979 after
China and the U.S. normalized their relations.
</P>
<P>
At present, he is engaged in two projects on finding
groundwater sources in Egypt and Oman by means of remote sensing
technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's PM Says His Visit to Iran not against US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan said here today that his visit to Iran is not against the
United States and has nothing to do with Americans.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his arrival at the airport, the Turkey's
pro-Islamic prime minister told reporters that "both Iran and the
United States are friends of Turkey and we would like to expand
our friendly ties with Iran just as we like with the United
States."
</P>
<P>
"Our trip here to the Islamic Republic of Iran has nothing to
do with the United States," said the visiting Turkish prime
minister while answering a question raised by Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said "This is my first foreign trip and I am very proud to
be here."
</P>
<P>
Tehran is the first leg of Erbakan's 10 day trip to four
Islamic countries, which also include Pakistan, Malaysia and
Indonesia. Erbakan is accompanied by a delegation of 250
high-ranking government officials and experts.
</P>
<P>
The United States has expressed displeasure to his visit at
this special moment -- five days after U.S. President Bill
Clinton signed the D'Amator bill which toughens sanctions against
Iran by punishing non-American companies that invest in Iran and
Libya's oil sectors.
</P>
<P>
Despite U.S. pressure, the 70-year-old Turkish prime minister
is to sign a 20 billion dollars gas deal with Iran Monday, which
will be the main agenda during his visit.
</P>
<P>
Based on the accord, Iran will export gas to Turkey for 22
years beginning from 1999.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two countries will also talk about the
issue on border security between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said: "We believe our ties with Iran should expand as
it should expand with all other countries."
</P>
<P>
After Iran, he added, "I will travel to the Western countries
and a number of other third world countries."
</P>
<P>
"We are here to expand our cooperation not just with respect
to gas but many other areas, such as machinery, power and trade."
</P>
<P>
He said: "I believe that as the main members of the Economic
Cooperation Organization (ECO), Iran, Turkey and Pakistan should
use the ECO vehicle to expand ties with other Islamic countries."
</P>
<P>
The ECO was founded by Iran, Turkey and Pakistan in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish prime minister is expected to hold talks with
Iranian leader Ali Khamenei and President Hashemi Rafsanjani in
the next two days.
</P>
<P>
Iran's First Vice-President Hassan Habibi said: "We are happy
to see Mr. Erbakan in Iran in his first foreign trip after his new
government came to power a few weeks ago."
</P>
<P>
"We have had good ties with Turkey ever since the victory of
the Islamic Revolution in Iran," he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "Iran and Turkey should promote peace in the
region as well as maintain secure borders."
</P>
<P>
Iran hailed Erbakan's visit to Tehran today as an important
political and economic victory in its efforts to thwart the
political isolation and economic sanctions by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iranian press published editorials, saying that the arrival of
a seasoned Turkish leader such as Prime Minister Erbakan in Iran
is a matter of real delectation for the Iranian nation and
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian press praised Turkey's independent foreign policy,
saying that "Turkish independent foreign policy will definitely be in
the interest of Turkey and other regional countries, especially
its neighbors."  
</P>
</TEXT>
