<HEADLINE> Mahdi Accuses Ethiopia of Invading Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Somali faction leader Ali
Mahdi Mohamed today condemned the alleged Ethiopian invasion of
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in north Mogadishu, Mahdi said his
faction is sending an official complaint to the United Nations,
the Organization of African Unity, the Arab League and the
Islamic Conference over what he called the unjustifiable attack
on Somalia's soil.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi said Ethiopia is benefiting from the anarchy in Somalia
and called for their total withdrawal, saying, ''if they're
fighting against the fundamentalists, they should confine their
job inside Ethiopia.''
</P>
<P>
''Somalis needs peace, not further disturbance and especially
not from Ethiopia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Fighting erupted yesterday between the Somali National Front
(SNF), formerly of the late Somali dictator Mohamed Siad Barre
and the Al-It-Had Islamic fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian planes, backing the SNF, allegedly carried out raids
against the fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
As Chairman of Somali Salvation Alliance (ssa), Mahdi strongly
denied his faction is taking part in the Ethiopian "aggression"
along with its ally the Somali National Front (SNF).
</P>
<P>
This invasion is a purely provocative action by the Ethiopian
government, he said, noting that ''Ethiopia has no right to fight
anybody in Somalia''as the fundamentalists will not come onto
power.
</P>
<P>
He said he received reports that 13 Al-Itihad Al-Islam
officials were killed when the Ethiopian forces destroyed the
largest al-Itihad base at Luq including Mosques in the town.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of civilians at the region of Gredo were either
killed or wounded as thousands of families have fled their homes,
he charged.
</P>
<P>
According to a field radio, Goldogob district has also been
attacked by Ethiopian fighter planes supported by infantry. But
no casualties were reported at this stage, the sources said,
adding the fighting still continues in the area.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian fighter planes had also been seen in el-Barde and
Bakol region of southern Somalia, but no fighting had erupted in
those areas, although dozens of people have started fleeing the
area, said the radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
