<HEADLINE> India's Paper Industry In Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- India's paper industry is
faced with a severe crisis following large-scale imports of
writing and printing paper, which has forced paper mills either to
drastically reduce or even to stop production, the Indian Express
said today.
</P>
<P>
The Hindustan Newsprint Limited based in Kottyam of Kerala
State has become the first victim of this crisis when it stopped
production last week.
</P>
<P>
J.P. Choudhury, chairman of the Titagarh Paper Mills and an
important member of the Indian Paper Mills Association, said here
Friday that almost all the paper mills in the country are carrying
large unsold stock and if no immediate steps were taken the paper
industry would collapse.
</P>
<P>
He demanded raising of the import duty on printing and writing
paper to at least 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Indian Paper Mills Association complained
Friday that the government has ignored the demand of the paper
industry to impose a higher duty on imported paper in this year's
budget.  
</P>
