<HEADLINE> Quake, flu trim Japanese life expectancy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 10(Xinhua)-- Japanese life expectancy -- still
the world's best -- has had its first decline in years because of
the killer quake in western Japan and a massive outbreak of
inf1uenza.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Health and Welfare Ministry reported today.
that life expectancy for Japanese females dropped 0.14 of a year
in 1995, from the previous year's average of to 82.84 years, the
first fall in seven years. The expected span for Japanese women
was, however, still the longest in the world after 11 consecutive
years.
</P>
<P>
The expected life span for men, also the world's longest,
declined for the first time in three years, by 0.21 of a year to
76.36 years.
</P>
<P>
The disastrous earthquake that struck Kobe and nearby areas in
January 1995 killed more than 6,300 people.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said this trimmed the expected life span for men
and women by 0.08 of a year and 0.12 of a year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The longevity gap between men and women widened by 0.07 of a
year from the previous year, hitting a record high of 6.48 years,
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It said Sweden ranked second in longevity with 81.38 years for
women and 76.08 for men, followed by Hong Kong with 81.16 years
for women and 75.84 years for men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
