<HEADLINE> India to Set up Financial Surveillance System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI), the country's central bank, is initiating steps to
introduce a surveillance system for the financial institutions and
non-banking financial companies in the country, the Indian Express
said today.
</P>
<P>
RBI Deputy Governor S.P. Talwar said here on Friday that the
setting up of the Board for Financial Supervision and the
Department of Supervision will be a major step towards this end.
</P>
<P>
The two new bodies will have an exclusive supervisory focus on
the entire spectrum of financial entities ranging from commercial
banks and financial institutions to non-banking financial
companies.
</P>
<P>
Besides on-site inspection, which until recently was the major
tool of RBI supervision over the banking system, a system of
off-site surveillance based on a prudential reporting system has
also been introduced, he said.
</P>
<P>
Walwar said RBI is also working on improving the efficacy of
the concurrent audit system that covered 50 percent of banks'
business operations and 100 percent of treasury operations to
facilitate early warning as regards errors and failures.  
</P>
