<HEADLINE> SADC Trade Protocol Document Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 10 (Xinhua) -- the two-day special
meeting of SADC's Industry and Trade Ministers' Committee ended
here on Friday, with most of the work relating to the
finalization of the SADC trade protocol completed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to newsmen in the city last evening, Executive
Secretary of the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
Kaire Mbuende said the meeting was convened to consider the draft
of the SADC trade protocol with a view to its finalization.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende explained that the trade protocol was one of the legal
instruments that will be submittedion to SADC summit to be held in
Maseru, Lesotho on August 24, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Other protocols that will be submitted for consideration by
the summit are energy protocol, transport and communication
protocol and protocol on combating illicit drug trafficking on
the SADC region, according to the executive secretary.
</P>
<P>
He said in considering the draft of the trade protocol, the
ministers agreed that the free trade area should be established
withintedion the next eight years after signing the trade protocol.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende clarified that the main objective of the protocol is
to establish a SADC Free Trade Area (FTA) to allow for free
movement of goods and services within the SADC region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that apart from creating a regional
market -- the SADC free trade area, the community is also
expected to open up the region to both domestic and foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende also revealed that the 12 SADC countries were keen at
cooperating with other African countries especially the east
African countries which are closer to the regional grouping.
</P>
