<HEADLINE> King Hussein to Visit Saudi Arabia Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan is
scheduled to visit Saudi Arabia Sunday for talks with King Fahd
on bilateral ties, ways to boost Arab solidarity and means to
revive the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein's visit was first announced by the Jordanian
government Tuesday, one day after the monarch held talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Amman, the first
visit to the kingdom by the Israeli prime minister since he won
the elections in May.
</P>
<P>
On the political front, King Hussein is expected to brief King
Fahd and other Saudi leaders on the status of the peace process,
the outcome of his talks with Netanyahu Monday and his talks with
Palestinian leaders Yasser Arafat in Aqaba Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On the bilateral level, the Jordanian monarch is expected to
discuss with the Saudi leadership further means to boost Jordanian-
Saudi economic cooperation and coordination of positions on
various issues concerned.
</P>
<P>
Tension in the Gulf following the two bombings in Saudi Arabia
targeting U.S. troops stationed there last November and this June
and the ongoing U.S.-Iran exchange of accusations are also
expected to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said that Jordan had received an assurance that
King Fahd will meet with King Hussein during his coming visit to
Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein did not meet King Fahd during his visit to Saudi
Arabia in February because the Saudi monarch was recovering from
an ailment, but held talks with Crown Prince Abdullah and other
Saudi leaders instead.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the two monarchs will be the first after
the 1990 Gulf crisis when relations were strained as a result
of the perceived Jordanian support for Iraq, which invaded Kuwait
in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
Their ties have been improved and given a strong boost since
the signing of a trade accord between the two countries in June.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein's planned meeting with the Saudi leaders is the
latest in a series of intense diplomatic contacts after Netanyahu
proposed the so-called "Lebanon first" option to Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad, who categorically rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian side insisted on the link between the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks of negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said a proposal was being floated to convene a
summit of the leaders of Saudi Arabia, Syria, Palestinians, Egypt
and Jordan to strengthen the Arab front in peace negotiations
with Israel and closely study ways and means to unlock the
stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
They said the summit could be held next week in Alexandria,
Egypt, but Jordanian officials could not confirm the reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
