<HEADLINE> Revenue Chief To Harmonize E. African Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Heads of the respective
revenue authorities in the East African Cooperation (EAC) member
countries will soon meet to seek ways of harmonizing customs
tariffs in the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing newsmen at Dar es Salaam Airport on Friday,
Minister of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation Jakaya
Kikwete said the agreement to proceed with harmonization
discussions was reached at a tripartite commission meeting in the
cooperation secretariat in Arusha early this week.
</P>
<P>
According to a press report today, the minister who led a
government delegation to mourn the death of former isles leader
Abdulrahman Mohamed Babu, said the commission agreed on the
harmonization of the tarrifs within the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Such a measure would smoothen monetary and commodity
transactions within the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
The EAC was revived in March this year after leaders of
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania launched the ECA secretariat at
Arusha in northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Harmonization of fiscal policies in east Africa would
stabilize exchange rates and lower the pace of inflation, he
said, adding that full convertibility of national currencies
would on work when traders had confidence in the currencies of
their trading partners.
</P>
<P>
"The tripartite commission meeting has endorsed the
convertability of east African currencies effectively July 1," he
affirmed. The three central banks had been directed to start the
implementation process, he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister promised to ensure that the road network
joining the partner states is in good condition, saying the
meeting endorsed the East African Road Network project set to
redefine more than 15 roads.
</P>
<P>
A secretariat for the project would be formed to make sure
that the project was implemented in the appropriate manner, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete said the three countries also agreed to introduce a
single passport to simplify the movement of citizens within the
region.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting also agreed on putting a counter for East African
Citizens in each of the airports in the tripartite area," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete further said that the cooperation commission similarly
suggested the introduction of an East African Flag. He added it
also decided that henceforth all commission meetings would be
held in Arusha, Northern Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
