<HEADLINE> HK SAR Preparatory Committee Approves Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The fourth plenary session of
the Preparatory Committee of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region closed here today, with adoption of three documents.
</P>
<P>
The documents involve how to form the Selection Committee for
the establishment of the first government of the Hong Kong SAR; a
proposal for implementing Clause Two of Article 24 of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong SAR, which is about defining the meaning of
permanent residents of the SAR; and a proposal on provisional use
of regional flags and regional emblems of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the closing ceremony, Qian Qichen,
vice-premier and chairman of the preparatory committee, said that
approval of specific methods on forming the Selection Committee
indicates that preparations for the establishment of the Hong Kong
SAR are near implementation.
</P>
<P>
The Selection Committee's task will be to select the first
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong SAR and to elect the provisional
Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Preparatory Committee will concentrate its
efforts on forming a Selection Committee of 400 permanent Hong
Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed the hope that every Preparatory Committee member
and all staff members of the secretariat will try his or her best
to do everything well and effectively to ensure the formation of
the Selection Committee in November.
</P>
<P>
The process of forming the Selection Committee needs assistance
from the British Hong Kong government in some matters, Qian said,
noting that "we hope that the British side will keep its promise
in this regard to show its sincerity to cooperate with its
actions."
</P>
<P>
Wang Hanbin, vice-chairman of the preparatory committee,
presided over today's meeting, and Lu Ping, vice-chairman and
secretary-general of the committee, gave a report on future work
to be done.
</P>
<P>
Reta Fan, head of the celebration activity panel briefed the
participants on the work involved in setting up a committee in
charge of celebrations for the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland on July 1, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
