<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Impending Decree to Boost Nigeria's Manufacturers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's federal government is
to promulgate the failed parastatals and companies decree to
promote the development of the country's manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
As part of the government efforts to continue sanitizing the
nation's economy, the new decree will complement the failed banks
(recovery of debts) and financial malpractices in banks decree.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected to guarantee national and international
confidence in Nigeria's industrial sector and stimulate
unhindered economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In a message delivered Friday at the opening ceremony of the
ninth national council on industry meeting, Head of State General
Sani Abacha said the federal parastatals decree has become
necessary since industry is the catalyst for the overall economic
development of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to General Abacha, the industrial sector has the
''potentials to compete in relative importance with the oil and
agricultural sectors in terms of poverty alleviation, employment
generation, wealth creation and raising our national per capita
income.''
</P>
<P>
He said that the government's 1996 budget has an array of
incentives to stabilize the business environment for long-term
and self sustaining growth as a strategy for developing the
manufacturing industry and other key production areas of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Abacha listed 12 priority areas such as foundries, forges,
sugar and sugar confectioneries, grains and cereals, vegetable
oil, livestock and allied products, wearing apparel, leather and
leather products, and building materials with focus on ceramics,
bricks and glass.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Industries Minister Lt.-Gen. Mohammed Haladu
said the major objective of the current government industrial
policy is to increase the local contents of industrial outputs.
</P>
<P>
According to him, identified raw materials will be developed
to substitute current imports and the government, through
policies and incentives materials, encourages established
industries to use such materials.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government has shifted its focus from
large scale industries to small and medium enterprises (SMES),
which are believed to be a better instrument for industrial
development in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program (UNDP) has budgeted
more than 16.7 million US Dollars for Nigeria's four-year SMES
development program, the minister said, adding that the country's
counterpart cash contribution to the program is 26.25 million
Naira (about 3.1 million Dollars) for 1996.
</P>
<P>
The national council on industry is the highest policy
generating body on industry in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
