<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 10 (Xinhua) - Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today appointed Alexander Lebed, Secretary of Russian Security
Council, as his new representative in Chechnya, said presidential
spokesman Sergei Medvedev.
</P>
<P>
Lebed replaced Oleg Lobov, who was appointed in August 1995,
when the heavy fighting between Chechen rebels and federal troops
for the control of the Chechen capital Grozny entered a fifth day.
</P>
<P>
Lebed would be the main authority in Chechnya along with Doku
Zavgayev, who is the head of the pro-Russian government in the
republic.
</P>
<P>
Lebed, who joined Yeltsin's team and helped him win the
presidential elections last July, has been criticizing Russia's
past policy in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
According to Lebed, force was not the only way to solve the
Chechen crisis, and only the withdrawal of Chechen fighters from
Grozny could make it possible for a ceasefire and peace in the
republic.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Russian authorities in Chechnya was criticized by
President Yeltsin, who said that they had committed serious errors
in their dealings with the rebel leaders. 
</P>
