<HEADLINE> Kuwait Draws up Plan to Encourage Recruitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is considering to
encourage its youths to join the Armed Forces through new
incentives with special allocations expected to be added up to
the military budget, according to a senior army officer.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Staff of the Kuwaiti Armed Forces General Ali
Al-Moumen said in an interview with the local Arabic language
daily Al-Anbaa published today that "we have worked out programs
including incentives to encourage Kuwaiti citizes to join the
Armed Forces."
</P>
<P>
He indicated that special budgets should be allocated in order
to implement these plans which he said were aimed at increasing
salaries of the servicemen, granting them more bonuses and
improving social care services for the retired.
</P>
<P>
The living standard of the families of the servicemen are
expected to be improved under the new plans, he added.
</P>
<P>
On troops education, the general said the military authorities
had arranged a contract with the Kuwait University to encourage
the youths in the army to carry out their higher education.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Defense Minister Sheikh Ahmed al-Humoud al-Sabah said
late July that Kuwaiti soldiers are now possessing high
capabilities to confront dangers and challenges, adding that the
armament budget would not be affected by a planned eradication of
the state budget deficit which is expected to remain at about 4
billion U.S. dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Kuwait army would attract more
youths by providing them incentives to encourage them.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has been the world's biggest spender on defense in per
capita terms since its 1991 liberation from the Iraqi occupation,
during which its military plants and equipment were destroyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
