<HEADLINE> Roundup: Turkish PM Sets off for Iran Despite US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkish pro-Islamic Welfare
Party (RP) Chairman and Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan this
morning embarked upon his first foreign visit to neighboring Iran
despite a warning from the United States.
</P>
<P>
This shows the determination of the Turkish coalition
government led by Erbakan for the further development of the
relations with the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
In Tehran, the local press today hailed Erbakan's visit to Iran
as an important political and economic victory in that country's
efforts to thwart the political isolation and economic sanctions
by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan's foreign trip will also take him to Pakistan,
Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
The main goal of his tour is to establish new economic and
commercial links between Turkey and these countries. Erbakan sees
great benefits in Turks' forging close ties with other Moslem
countries which he feels will contribute to Turkey's development
effort.
</P>
<P>
In Tehran, the first stop of his foreign tour, Erbakan wants
to step up cooperation with the Iranian government in many areas
including oil, gas and aviation.
</P>
<P>
During Erbakan's visit in Iran, Ankara and Tehran are expected
to sign a gas agreement worth 20 billion U.S. dollars. The 23-year
agreement will involve the sale of 4 billion cubic meters of gas
annually, which will be increased gradually to 10 billion cubic
meters by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is scheduled to go into effect in 1999 after the
construction of a 260-kilometer pipeline from the Iranian city of
Tabriz to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Turkey and Iran is expected to be
increased from last year's 950 million dollars to 2 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan also intends to assure the Iranians that Turks are
friends and neighbors and will remain so irrespective of outside
pressures.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton signed the d'Amato-Kennedy law on
Monday to reinforce embargoes against Iran and Libya by
dissuading foreign companies and individuals from investing
heavily in the oil industries of the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
