<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Turkish PM Sets off for Iran Despite US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A senior U.S. senator has urged Secretary of State Warren
Christopher to help find a replacement for Turkey's proposed
20-billion-dollar natural gas deal with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Turkish State Minister Abdullah Gul, main aide of Erbakan,
said, "Turkey is not in a position to ask the U.S.,'Would you veto
this or not?' on all its foreign policy issues, demanding
permission. Turkey is an independent country. It has its own
interests."
</P>
<P>
Iran attaches great importance to Erbakan's visit, especially
since the U.S. passed the law that would impose sanctions on
countries investing in Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati has said that
Erbakan has always adopted a friendly stance toward Iran and
since he is in favor of having cordial ties with the Islamic
states, "we are looking forward to seeing more friendly ties
between Iran and Turkey in future."
</P>
<P>
Velayati made the remarks immediately after the Turkish
coalition government between the RP and True Path Party (DYP) led
by Erbakan won the vote of confidence in the parliament in July.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Aladdin Burujerdi said in the
border city of Meshed Thursday that under the Turkish coalition
government led by Erbakan, the Iranian-Turkish relations would
reach a "turning point."
</P>
<P>
Burujerdi indicated that minor issues of border security could
be easily solved with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
This was a reference to the frequent complaint by Turkey that
the rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) use the
Turkish-Iranian border freely to strike at Turkish military and
civilian targets and then escape into Iran where they are said to
have bases and camps.
</P>
<P>
As a gesture prior to Erbakan's visit to Iran, Tehran had
invited Turkish officials in the past weeks to Iran and conduct
their own inspections in the border areas with Turkey following
the complaints by Ankara of the PKK attacks from the Iranian soil.
</P>
<P>
The two sides "also discussed enhancing of security along the
borders of the two countries," the official Iranian news agency
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Some observers here fear that Turkey and the U.S. might be on a
collision course over relations with Iran, since Erbakan and
Washington are adamant in their opposing positions on Iran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
