<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects US Claim of Helping Iraq Export Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today
rejected the U.S. claim that Tehran helped Iraq smuggle oil
products through southern Iran.
</P>
<P>
Kamal Kharrazi, Iranian representative to the United Nations,
was quoted by the official news agency IRNA as saying that "such
accusations are part of Washington's propaganda campaign against
Iran."
</P>
<P>
Iran will prove the inaccuracy of the baseless U.S. accusations
if the U.N. Security Council's sanction committee considers
necessary, he added.
</P>
<P>
The claim, which was first raised by the U.S. Administration
about a month ago by sending a letter to the head of the U.N.
Security Council's sanctions committee, is as unsubstantiated and
unfounded as its earlier claims, Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
Washington claimed that ships carrying smuggled Iraqi oil
entered the Iranian coastal waters through the northern part of
the Gulf and the international waters and then proceeded to the
southern part, avoiding the allied forces.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has also claimed that the operation is carried out
with the knowledge of the Iranian government and by charging the
Iraqi ships.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi denied that Iran has violated the U.N. sanctions
imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, reiterating
that Iran was compelled to beef up its patrol and coastal units in
Arvand river and the Gulf borders in order to exercise a better
surveillance for effective implementation of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he added, Iran has submitted the registered
cases of violation of Iraqi sanctions with the supporting
documents to the U.N. special committee.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that in a letter to the Security Council's
committee on sanctions on December 16, 1994, Iran reported
several cases of violation of embargo on Iraq including hoisting
of the Iranian flag by smugglers for carrying their shipment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
