<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 08:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Lowers Charges for Goods at Aqaba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has decided to lower
charges for handling goods at the south Red Sea Port of Aqaba,
the English-language daily Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to Captain Mohammad Dlabeeh, the new director-general
of the Ports Corporation, the reductions in service charges
approved recently by the cabinet would lower the overall cost for
each 20-feet container to nearly 66 dinars (about 92.4 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Handling expenses were lowered by 20 percent and loading and
unloading charges by 25 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
As to vegetables and fruits, charges were reduced by 42
percent while the reduction for frozen food was 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the lowered charges would make the Aqaba port a real
and strong competitor to all ports on the Red Sea and would
enable it to become a center for vessels and large containers for
re-export to neighboring ports.
</P>
<P>
The ports corporation chief said that many international
companies were holding contacts with the corporation to route
their vessels to Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
He expected that there will be a large increase in handling
volume during the coming period as a result of the lower charges.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of this year, the volume of
exports and imports through Aqaba exceeded 6.5 million tonnes, of
which 3.8 million tonnes were phosphate, fertilizers and potash.
</P>
<P>
Various imports amounted to 2.6 million tonnes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Dlabeeh added that Jordan had agreed with the Suez
Canal Authority officials to take similar reduction on goods
passing through the canal to the Port of Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
"We will soon conduct discussions with Egyptian officials to
arrive at a final agreement with regard to making the similar
reductions," said Dlabeeh.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will start implementing the lower charges in the coming
few days after the cabinet decision is published in the official
gazette.
</P>
<P>
The captain revealed that the corporation would be implementing
many projects to activate the port and such projects will be
announced soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
