<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Physicals on Malaysia's
Crude Palm Oil (CPO) market closed higher this week on news that
China will issue import licenses to its palm oil producers.
</P>
<P>
The market opened lower on Monday as buyers waited for private
forecaster Ivan Wang's forecast for July's estimated production
and rebounded the next day.
</P>
<P>
But it dropped on Wednesday following bearish data released by
Ivan Wong who reported that end-July production of oil palm is
estimated to increase 2.8 percent to 742,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The market rebounded again on Thursday and saw the August South
close higher at 1,110 ringgit (about 444 U.S. dollars) per ton
this week, compared with 1,090 ringgit (about 436 U.S. dollars)
previously.
</P>
<P>
The Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) closed the week lower after
a nine-sen (3.6 U.S. cents) drop on Friday, which erased all gains
made earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
The drop on Friday was due to the lack of buying interests in
the local market and too much supply offered by sellers.
</P>
<P>
The metal finished the week at 15.06 ringgit (about 6.024 U.S.
dollars) per kilogram, compared with 15.15 ringgit (about 6.06
U.S. dollars) previously.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover for the week was 444 tons, against 498
tons previously, with the Europeans, Japanese and locals
accounting for the week's transactions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, The Malaysian rubber market ended the week slightly
lower as inquiries from overseas were lacking following summer
holidays in major consuming countries.
</P>
<P>
Both September RSS one and SMR 20 dropped by 1.5 sen (0.6 U.S.
cents) each to close at 324.50 sen (about 129.8 U.S. cents) per
kilogram and 303.50 sen (about 121.4 U.S. cents) per kilogram
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
