<HEADLINE> Farm Unions Oppose Free Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Organized agriculture in
Namibia, South Africa, Zambia and Zimbabwe would +strenuously
resist+ a proposed South African-European free trade agreement
affecting the beef industry in the region.
</P>
<P>
This was said by the Southern African Confederation of
Agricultural Unions (SACAU) in a statement issued in Windhoek,
Namibia on Friday.
</P>
<P>
At an urgent meeting in Harare, Zimbabwe on Thursday, SACAU
said it +noted with deep concern+ the mandate of the commission
of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
In particular, SACAU has recognized the potential consequences
of this mandate in so far as the production of agricultural
commodities, especially beef, is concerned both in South Africa
and in its adjacent trading partners,+ said the statement.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was currently negotiating with the European Union
(EU) about a free trade agreement, but the proposed pact had
already caused some concern in its neighboring countries,
especially in the field of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
SACAU said the mandate would have a +deleterious if not
devastated effect+ upon the beef production sector in southern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
SACAU urged the 12 Southern African Development Community
(SADC) countries to study the mandate and inform themselves of
its implications.
</P>
<P>
SACAU said it +wishes to make public its support for South
African agriculture in resisting any form of unfair competition,
subsidized imports or dumping so as to maintain its own beef
production sector+.
</P>
<P>
SACAU also stressed that any agreement allowing subsidized
agricultural production in developed countries to supplant
commercial production in the region, particular in the beef
sector, +must be construed as being contrary to the interests of
agricultural development in the region as a whole and will be
strenuously resisted+. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
