<HEADLINE> NATO Enlargement Not to Bring Much Cost: German Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The eastward expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) should not cost too much
money, German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe said today.
</P>
<P>
Advanced planes and tanks should not be the preconditions for
East European countries to join the NATO, Ruehe told the press
while accompanying Canadian Defense Minister David Collenette to
visit Berlin.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent Pentagon-commissioned report, NATO might
have to pay 42 billion U.S. dollars over the next 10 to 15 years
for its eastward expansion to include four new members -- Poland,
the Czech Republic, Slovakia and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe expressed his doubt over the report, saying that some of
the NATO's 65 commands should be closed in order to reduce the
financial burden of the NATO members.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe held talks today with Collenette, who was on a two-day
visit beginning Thursday, on the issue of the NATO's
restructuring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand to Use Tariff Cuts as Bargaining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will use its offer to
lower tariffs as a bargaining tool to persuade other members of
the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) to remove non-tariff
barriers on agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has decided to use proposed cuts in Thai tariffs as a
chip for bargaining greater market access for Thai farm exports.
</P>
<P>
Observers see the move as a marked shift in the approach to
APEC's trade and investment liberalization plans, which call for
lowering trade barriers voluntarily without bargaining.
</P>
<P>
Basically an agricultural economy, Thailand will focus its
interest on agriculture, which supports the livelihood of three
quarters of the population and is still a main foreign exchange
earning sector.
</P>
<P>
Considering the value added, agricultural products benefit the
country no less than industrial products.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay Virawan, who oversees economic
affairs, has said "We want to call for mutual benefits. If they
(the other 17 APEC members) give us unsuitable benefits, we won't
give them much either."
</P>
<P>
In particular, Thailand wants to see non-tariff barriers, such
as quotas, and other measures removed on farm goods.
</P>
<P>
In this respect Thailand is concerned about Japanese and South
Korean rice quotas, which will come under particular scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
Also targeted would be policies that use product standards,
environmental criteria, public health and anti-dumping taxes to
curb imports, because these hurt Thai agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is now closely watching its counterparts' individual
action plans to be tabled at the APEC senior officials' meeting,
scheduled for August 21 in Davao, the Philippines, to see whether
their plans means rules and regulations will remain obstacles to
Thai exports, including in particular farm products.
</P>
<P>
Thai agricultural exports include rice, rubber, tapioca, sugar,
coffee and fruit.
</P>
<P>
Although APEC's 18 members have said that they want to lower
their trade barriers voluntarily without bargaining, they are
looking at each other's plans and they have agreed that the plans
should be 'comparable.'
</P>
<P>
Some countries such as the United States have not ruled out the
possibility of negotiations in the future.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Malaysia is one of the staunchest opponents
of any form of bargaining in APEC.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization's plans are being drafted for the APEC leaders'
informal meeting in the Philippines in November.
</P>
<P>
Trade barriers would start to fall under the plans from January
1, leading to liberalized trade and investment by 2010 for
developed members and 2020 for developing members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 08:23 </DATE_TIME>
