<HEADLINE> Nigerian Workers Calls for Cut in Excise Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's food workers have
called on the federal government to reduce excise tax on products
of the food, tobacco and beverage subsector from 40 to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
John Onyenemere, President of the National Union of Tobacco,
Food and Beverage Employees, said here Friday that the reduction
will go a long way to salvage the deteriorating situation in the
industry and help create employment opportunities for unemployed
Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government to assist this sector from
collapse by reactivating them with soft loans so that the workers
sacked can be reabsorbed.
</P>
<P>
The union chief also urged big companies to stop incessant
retrenchment of workers.
</P>
<P>
Due to consumer resistance and lack of purchasing power, the
industry has been distressed for some time after ware houses have
been filled up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
