<HEADLINE> Iran Hails Erbakan's Visit in Defiance of US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran hailed the visit by Turkish
Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan to Tehran today as an important
political and economic victory in its efforts to thwart the
political isolation and economic sanction by the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian press published editorials today, claiming the
arrival of pro-Islamic Turkish prime minister in Iran is a matter
of real delectation for the Iranian nation and authorities.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily Iran News said that a red carpet
welcome by the administration of President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani awaits the Turkish prime minister, who is expected to
arrive this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
An editorial by the daily said, "Iran welcomes Prime Minister
Erbakan in Tehran as an experienced politician who commands an
Islamic and independent thinking," adding, "Tehran will do all
that is needed to solidify the government of Prime Minister
Erbakan."
</P>
<P>
Another English-language daily Tehran Times in its editorial,
entitled "Erbakan's Visit Signals Time to Form United Islamic
Front," called on Islamic countries to march ahead shoulder to
shoulder to build a united Islamic front.
</P>
<P>
It said that it is the natural right of Iran and Turkey to
expand mutual cooperation and lay the foundation for multilateral
cooperation involving other regional countries.
</P>
<P>
The editorial praised Turkey's foreign policy, saying "the
Turkish independent foreign policy will definitely be in the
interests of Turkey and other regional countries, especially of
its neighbors."
</P>
<P>
During Erbakan's visit, Iran and Turkey will sign a
20-billion-dollar gas deal. Under the accord, Iran will export gas
to Turkey for 22 years beginning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times claimed the deal is to be signed "in defiance" of
the sanction law signed by U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, regarding the issues of the Turkish Workers' Party
(PKK), Iran News added, "The most significant and caustic issue is
related to claims in some Turkish circles of Iran's alleged
support for the PKK. In the light of its prevailing foreign
policy, Iran is always prepared to investigate such allegations."
</P>
<P>
In the future as in the past, it said, "Iran will never
support terrorists whoever they may be."
</P>
<P>
In return, the editorial said, "Iran expects reciprocation from
Turkey in connection with terrorist groups which occasionally
raise their heads against the Islamic Republic." 
</P>
</TEXT>
