<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Afghanistan on Edge of Hyperinflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Still entangled in ceaseless
fighting among feuding factions after 17 years of war, Afghanistan
is now tottering on the brink of hyperinflation, which is
devastating to its economic life.
</P>
<P>
Economists listed high costs, increasing demand and an
inflationary spiral of rising prices and wages as direct causes
for the country's sky-rocketing prices.
</P>
<P>
They noted that Afghanistan's worst economic disaster is the
result of years of fighting, economic blockade, collapse of social
and economic institutions, absence of appropriate banking and
monetary policies, diminishing domestic production and declining
agriculture yield.
</P>
<P>
The country's currency has been depreciated drastically,
registering almost daily falls from 37.90 Afghanis against one
U.S. dollar in 1978 to 5,500 Afghanis in January this year, and
then to an astonishing level of 15,000 Afghanis in June.
</P>
<P>
That means that the Afghani has lost its value by approximately
396 times during the past 17 years and by more than 2.7 times in
the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Many economists fear that if the present situation continues,
Afghans will have to return to a barter transaction system, which
will be extremely dangerous to those who do not possess any means
of production.
</P>
<P>
The rapid increase in money supply has created a yawning budget
deficit, a virtual economic collapse, and increasing inflationary
expectations which will work dreadful economic and social havoc in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Budget deficit is believed to be the mother of all economic
diseases and by the time the situation improves, Afghans will
still have to spend many of their resources on paying debts.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan is now importing almost all consumer items,
including wheat, flour, sugar and cement, and in significantly
larger volumes than the pre-war amounts.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign trade has been badly affected as its
borders are now under the control of different groups who are
totally independent from the central government.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that Afghanistan is in a crying need of
strong and stable government capable of implementing effective
monetary and fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
However, as a "strong and stable" administration seems to be
still in some far-off future, some economists have recommended the
establishment of an economic council comprising representatives
from all parties involved in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
They said that this council should be mandated to study the
overall situation in Afghanistan and recommend economic policies
aimed at curbing soaring inflation, reducing deficits, improving
balance of trade and boosting domestic production.
</P>
<P>
They added that the council should also encourage an
appropriate allocation of national resources by various forces and
collaborate with international organizations in the rehabilitation
of Afghanistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
