<HEADLINE> Two Turkish Ministers to Pay Official Visit to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Justice Minister Sevket
Kazan and Education Minister Mehmet Saglam are expected to pay an
official visit to Iraq Sunday and to meet with Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein, according to the local newspaper Sabah today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the two ministers would extend a message from
Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan to Saddam on the
settlement to the issue of the Turkish outlawed Kurdish Worker's
Party (PKK) in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels often strike at the military and civilian
targets in Turkey and then escape into northern Iraq, where they
are said to have bases and camps.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish ministers will also hold talks with Iraqi
officials on the reopening of the Kerkuk-Yumurtalik pipeline and
Turkey's sale of food and medicine to Iraq, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the Iraqi sanctions committee under the U.N.
Security Council approved the procedures for implementing the
oil-for-food deal between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
According to Resolution 986 of the U.N. Security Council, Iraq
will be able to sell oil worth 2 billion U.S. dollars over six
months and purchase food, medicine and other necessities for its
people so as to alleviate the effect of the six-year long
sanctions imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
