<HEADLINE> New Swazi Prime Minister Inaugurated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland's
newly-appointed Prime Minister Barnabas Dlamini was on Friday
inaugurated as the kingdom's 8th prime minister since its
independence in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his inauguration ceremony at his official
residence in Mbabane, Dlamini said the new Swazi government's
agenda would be open and accountable for its deeds, reported +the
Citizen+ daily today.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini said open government meant upholding the rule of law
and a willingness to be bound by its obligations.
</P>
<P>
+No one group is beyond the law,+ he added.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini, 54, a former finance minister before taking up an
appointment as a director of the World Bank/International
Monetary Fund's African region in 1992, was appointed as the
prime minister by the monarch King Mswati iii on July 26 to
succeed former prime minister Prince Mbilini Dlamini.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dlamini said the process of consultation, for which
he intended the new government to be known, had already started.
</P>
<P>
+This will be a continued and committed effort on my part to
ensure that our policies and programs are relevant to the
country's needs,+ said the prime minister, adding this was part
of the kingdom's tradition.
</P>
<P>
However, the consultation process would not be an excuse for
indecision, he added.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland is the only southern African country where political
parties have been banned since 1973, and the monarch king rules
the kingdom by royal decree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
