<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plant Useful for Family Planning in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Scientific researchers in Zambia
have discovereds a local plant whose active substance is effective
in family planning, controlling malaria, bilharzia and livestock
diseases.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was made by a team of ten headed by Mohammed
Shehata, a scientist in tropical public health at Zambia's
National Council for Scientific Research (NCSR) Kitwe office in
Copperbelt Province.
</P>
<P>
Zambia News Agency quoted Shehata, an Egyptian scientist
recruited by NCSR in 1985, as saying that it took his team 10
years to make the discovery in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The plant, endod or phytolacco in scientific terms, is also
available in Ethiopia, the Middle East and the United States. It
grows naturally in near sources of water like rivers, streams and
lakes.
</P>
<P>
The research findings show that berries produced by endod
contain about 25 percent of saponin, an active substance that is
effective in killing snails carrying the bilharzia parasite and
larvae of mosquitoes carrying malaria plasmodium.
</P>
<P>
''Saponin also kills sperms and can be used as a compound for
birth control,'' Shehata said.
</P>
<P>
Shehata and his team have over the years developed a
technology of extracting the substance from endod berries.
Saponin alone can be exported to pharmaceutical companies and
earn foreign exchange for Zambia, according to the Egyptian
scientist.
</P>
<P>
Shehata is heading a team in Chililabombwe of Copperbelt
Province to fight bilharzia which is spreading there with many
pupils of local primarybombwe schools affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 07:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Refuses Israel's "Lebanon First" Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has categorically refused
Israel's proposal on a unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon in
exchange for a disarmament of the Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas
and a deployment of the Lebanese army to the border area, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government reiterated Friday that the unity of the
Lebanese and Syrian positions would ensure the liberation of the
occupied lands and the realization of a just and comprehensive
peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi Friday night presided at an
extraordinary cabinet session to discuss the latest developments
on the domestic and regional levels.
</P>
<P>
On the top of the meeting's agenda was a bill revising the
contraversial election law, according to which the next
parliamentary election would be held in Lebanon later this month.
</P>
<P>
"At the beginning of the session, the president briefed the
Council of Ministers on his recent meeting with Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad" in Damascus last Monday, Minister of Agriculture
Shawki Fakhoury told reporters at the end of the cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the president reaffirmed Lebanon's solid
positions as sollowing:
</P>
<P>
First, the Lebanese and Syrian tracks are one track which has
the same goal, namely, the liberation of lands and the
establishment of a just and comprehensive peace.
</P>
<P>
Second, there is no room to separate or discriminate against
the Lebanese and Syrian tracks.
</P>
<P>
Third, Lebanon and Syria, as announced by the president on a
number of occasions, will enter the negotiations with a united
stand.
</P>
<P>
Forth, all what has been circulated on the "Lebanon First" is
unacceptable. Fakhoury said it is "because the unity of the
Lebanese and Syrian positions, in the negotiations and on the
results, ensures the achievements of our goals and the realization
of the two peoples' interests.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu repeated
his conditions for a withdrawal from a 15-kilometer-wide occupied
enclave in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Israeli forces would pull out of the Israeli
self-proclaimed "security zone" in south Lebanon only after the
disarmament of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah guerrillas, deployment of
the Lebanese army on the frontier and guaranteed security for
northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Syrian President Assad announced his refusal of the "Lebanon
First" proposal in Cairo Wednesday after meeting Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
To counter the Israeli initiative, Assad declared "Syria and
Lebanon first, at the same time and in the same steps." 
</P>
