<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stranded Waste to Be Returned to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 10 (Xinhua) -- The plastic waste rejected
earlier by China and stranded in Hong Kong will be returned
shortly to the United States for disposal, the Environmental
Protection Department (EPD) of Hong Kong announced today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said that EPD has requested the assistance of
Swire BFI Waste Services Ltd. in finding a solution to the
problem. Swire BFI has offered, in conjunction with their parent
company, Browning-Ferris Industries, to provide an appropriate
disposal solution.
</P>
<P>
Agreement has also been reached with Hong Kong trader, Chiang's
Brothers Company, that they will make arrangement for the
repackaging and transportation of the waste to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ellen Chan, Principal Environmental Protection Officer,
said: "The post consumer plastic waste was mixed with household
waste to an extent that recycling was not considered suitable."
</P>
<P>
He said that returning the waste to the exporting country for
disposal is the best solution to this problem.
</P>
<P>
The 200-ton plastic waste has to be rebaled and containerized
before shipment, which will be carried out in two lots. The first
shipment is scheduled to leave Hong Kong this evening and the next
shipment in about two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
