<HEADLINE> Only Peace Talks Can End Chechen Conflicts: Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Yeltsin, sworn
in today for the second term, said the Chechen conflicts could
only be ended by peace talks, describing the four-day rebels' raid
on the Chechen capital Grozny as a large-scale terrorist move.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorist attacks will be resolutely put down," Yeltsin said
in his first statement since fierce fighting re-erupted on
Tuesday, less than three months after he won a ceasefire during
talks with separatist leader Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev on May 27.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, even in this difficult situation, I continue to
insist there is no other way to settle the conflict in Chechnya
other than the peace negotiations I began on May 27," said Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
"I will not allow anybody to talk to the federal authorities in
the language of blackmail," he warned, while delivering
condolences to the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin today called for sending
specially-trained troops from the Interior Affairs Ministry and
Federation Security Ministry to quell the Grozny fighting.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government today also said in a statement that it
would make all efforts to halt the Grozny bloodshed and seize
Grozny again as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The rebels' raid on Grozny, aimed to destroy a stable Russia
and leading to the escalation of the Chechen war, was an offensive
on the whole international community, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports reaching here said fighting between Russian
troops and Chechen rebels in Grozny raged all day around the
headquarters of the pro-Moscow administration in Chechnya, which
both sides claimed to control late today.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 people have been killed since Russian soldiers
marched into the breakaway Caucasus republic in late 1994 to crack
down on a three-year independence drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
