<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD: Finnish Economy to Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Finland would see an economic
rebound next year on the basis of good performance in 1996,
according to the latest report released by the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
According to the OECD projections, Finland's GDP growth would
be about 2.4 percent this year due to the reversal of the forestry
goods export boom.
</P>
<P>
The exports growth would go up to about 3.5 percent next year,
with the expectation of this year to rebound across the board,
which would remain well ahead of the OECD area's average growth
rate of 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate, which was as high as 18.4 percent in
1994, has fallen to some 16.4 percent on average this year, and it
would moderately drop to 15.5 percent in 1997, the OECD forecast.
</P>
<P>
Inflation would remain well below 2 percent, while the current
account surplus, which reached 4.3 percent of GDP last year, could
fall back to 3.0 percent next year, mainly because of the sluggish
outlook in the world forestry market.
</P>
<P>
As for the reasons, the report said that the Finnish current
monetary policy framework, which was based on inflation target and
a floating exchange rate, has strengthened the confidence of the
country's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Finland, one of Europe's fastest-growing economies in 1994-95,
faced a temporary slowdown in the past year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
