<HEADLINE> Cyprus President Appeals Motorcyclists not to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides has called on motorcyclists, taking part in Sunday's
anti-Turkish occupation ride along the island's ceasefire line, to
avoid at all costs any confrontation with the U.N. and not to
enter the U.N. controlled buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a local festival Friday night, the president said
that the bikers will achieve their objective to inform the world
public opinion about the continuing Turkish occupation of Cyprus'
northern areas if there is no confrontation with the U.N.
peace-keeping forces which controls the 180-kilometer long buffer
zone, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The President warned against any incidents in the buffer zone
because such a development would convey the wrong message, he
said.
</P>
<P>
If there is confrontation, the president said, it would look
as if Greek and Turkish Cypriots cannot live together.
</P>
<P>
Should bikers get through to the buffer zone, they are likely
to be confronted by Turkish troops and possibly anti-ride
protesters, he said.
</P>
<P>
About 120 Cypriot and European bikers started a 10-day ride
from Berlin last Friday and will arrive at Limassol port of this
island this morning aboard a ship from Greece.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, they will be joined by about 7,000 Greek Cypriot
riders, and together they will stage a ride along the buffer
zone, and will attempt to ride to the northern coastal town of
Kyrenia.
</P>
<P>
Both the Cyprus government and the U.N. have warned against
trouble in the buffer zone during the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides urged the bikers to hand their protest
petition to the U.N. for free movement in Cyprus and the
withdrawal of Turkish troops.
</P>
<P>
This, Clerides believes, would have a better impact on would
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot press reported that the Turkish troops had
been ordered to shoot anyone who attempts to cross into the
Turkish-controlled northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Local police are taking all available means to avoid
confrontation and to ensure the status of the U.N.-controlled
buffer zone is not violated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
