<HEADLINE> Giraffes Get Skin Diseases in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- About 80 giraffes in Kabalega
national park of Uganda have been attacked by unidentified skin
diseases, reported +the New Vision+ daily today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Gladys Kalema, a veterinary doctor for Uganda wildlife
authority was quoted as saying that the diseases seem to infect
50 percent of adult giraffes while the younger ones are normal.
</P>
<P>
Kalema said she went to the park last month to collect skin
scrapes and biopsies and blood sample for examination.
</P>
<P>
She said the skin samples were sent to Makerere university in
Kampala and another blood sample sent to Zimbabwe for comparative
results.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory results will determine the disease and drugs to be
administered, said Kalema.
</P>
<P>
She said the skin diseases, which appear as round gray
hairless patches with a diameter of about 10 cm do not seem to
have affected the animal's health.
</P>
<P>
The patches tend to be more concentrated on white parts of the
skin especially on the animal's long neck and under the arm pits,
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
