<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Housing Secretary
and Republican Congressman Jack Kemp has accepted an offer by
U.S. presidential challenger Bob Dole as his vice presidential
running mate, the Cable News Network (CNN) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing Republican sources, the CNN said that Dole had called
Kemp to make the offer and Kemp accepted it.
</P>
<P>
With several new polls showing him trailing President Bill
Clinton by 20 points or more, Dole said that selecting a good
running mate is the most important choice in his campaign to win
the presidency in the general elections scheduled for November.
</P>
<P>
Kemp, 61, who served 18 years in the U.S. Congress representing
Buffalo, the state of New York, and was the housing secretary
under the former U.S. President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
Although he had a difficult relationship with Dole in the past,
Kemp indicated earlier in the day that he would be glad to become
Dole's running mate if he would be offered.
</P>
<P>
Dole and Kemp had a long meeting in Washington on Wednesday to
discuss the new strategy of the Republicans in the presidential
campaign throughout the country. 
