<HEADLINE> Prehistoric Fossils Found in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Mexican experts uncovered the
fossil remains of some 20 different animal species 88 million
years ago in southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The 1,400 pieces of fossils, found in the state of Guerrero on
the Pacific coast, are between 87 and 88.5 million years old, the
Guerrero Autonomous University (UAG) said today.
</P>
<P>
The UAG Institute of Scientific Studies stressed the scientific
importance of the findings -- remains of mollusks, sponges, corals
and echinoderms that can be located in the Higher Cretaceous
geological age.
</P>
<P>
The experts, who have been working on a prehistoric study for
five years, found the fossils near the Ahuexotitlan community of
the Chilapa municipality, some 300 kilometers south of the Mexican
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
