<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Legislators in Cuba for Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican Congress will continue
rejecting the U.S. Helms-Burton law, Senator Jose Murat reiterated
here today on his arrival for a Mexican-Cuban interparliamentary
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Murat, head of the Mexican delegation and vice president of the
Permanent Commission of the Congress, said that the Mexican
Congress is to draft a law against the Helms-Burton act, revealing
that several members of the Chamber of Deputies are already
working on it.
</P>
<P>
He noted that neither as Latin Americans nor as Mexicans will
the legislators permit actions that violate the sovereignty and
infringe upon the right of the peoples and governments in the
region to self-determination.
</P>
<P>
Murat also stressed the importance of the meeting between the
Mexican Congress and the Cuban National Assembly of the People's
Power, saying that the meeting, to be convened here August 10-11,
will become a firm gesture of solidarity between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The interparliamentary meeting will discuss the problems
arising from the U.S. Helms-Burton law, environmental issues,
bilateral economic and commercial relations and interparliamentary
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
This is the first of the regular meetings between the two
parliaments, which will be held alternatively in the two countries
on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican delegation consists of 25 legislators from the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, the National Action Party, the
Labor Party and the Democratic Revolutionary Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
