<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The following is a summary of
Latin American economic briefs.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's industrial activity increased 5.5
percent in the first five months of this year over the previous
same period and rose 13.2 percent in May over the same month last
year, the Finance Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's investment abroad reached 3.15 billion
U.S. dollars by June, the Central Bank of Chile said.
</P>
<P>
As much as 2.1 billion dollars went to South American
countries. Argentina is the main recipient of Chilean investment
with 1.36 billion dollars, followed by Peru with 270 million
dollars and Brazil with 184.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SAN SALVADOR -- El Salvador's foreign exchange reserve reached
a record high of 1 billion dollars by July, the Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The growth was attributed to the sustained increase of exports,
the remittances from Salvadorans working abroad, and the
disbursement of foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Foreign investment in Peru reached 5.678 billion
dollars by the end of July, the National Commission for Foreign
Investments and Technologies (Conite) said today.
</P>
<P>
Spain, the United Kingdom and the United States are the main
investors, accounting for 72.2 percent of foreign capital in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
