<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The following is a summary of
Latin American economic briefs:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina registered a trade surplus of 570
million U.S. dollars in the first half of the year, 31.5 percent
less than that in the same period of 1995, the National Statistics
and Census Institute (Indec) said.
</P>
<P>
The exports totaled 11.25 billion dollars and imports 10.68
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's foreign exchange reserve increased by 447
million U.S. dollars in July to 15.3 billion U.S. dollars, the
Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank attributed the increase to payments of the
country's loans and a positive adjustment in the value of
international assets.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The Brazilian auto industry turned out a
record high of 175,300 units in July, a 26.5 percent increase over
the previous month, the National Association of Motor Vehicle
Manufacturers said.
</P>
<P>
As many as 1,006,900 units are produced from January to July,
6.9 percent higher over the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
This year's production is expected to reach 1.9 million units,
a 13 percent increase over the 1.68 million units in 1995.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico posted a 4.13-billion-dollar trade
surplus in the first six months, a 29 percent rise over the same
period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
This surplus resulted from 45.47 billion dollars of exports and
41.34 billion dollars of imports, up 18.4 percent and 17.4 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's National Copper Corporation (Codelco) made
a profit of 684.7 million U.S. dollars in the first six months, 17
percent down from the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Codelco's vice-president Marcos Lima explained that the fall
was due to a plunge in copper price.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The swath of destruction left by Hurricane Cesar
will cut Nicaragua's coffee production by 64 percent, or 685,000
quintals, expected for the 96-97 season, the Nicaraguan Coffee
Producers Union said.
</P>
<P>
The biggest damage caused by the hurricane to coffee production
was reported from Matagalpa and Jinotega, two major coffee
producing provinces of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
