<HEADLINE> Gurkha Soldiers Demands Equal Treatment from Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's former Gurkha
soldiers, who had served in the British army, have accused the
British government of violating a 1947 tripartite treaty by
treating them discriminately.
</P>
<P>
A group of ex-Gurkha servicemen told a press conference Friday
that they have requested Nepali Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba
to take up their four-point demands with the British government.
</P>
<P>
"We want justice from the British government," said chairman of
 the Ex-Gurkha Association Padam Bahadur Gurung.
</P>
<P>
According to him, under the 1947 tripartite treaty between
Britain, India and Nepal on the Gurkha troops, the Nepali soldiers
in the British army could enjoy the same treatment as their
British counterparts.
</P>
<P>
But actually Gurkha soldiers don't enjoy the privileges granted
to British soldiers, he said,.
</P>
<P>
Former Gurkha soldiers, mostly from northern Nepal's hilly
areas, said that they got pensions barely adequate for survival
after returning home from their service in the British army.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Nepali Gurkhas fought for Britain during World War
II, but they were sent home with 'money just enough to travel
home', the ex-Gurkhas said.
</P>
<P>
According to them, British ex-servicemen with same ranks can
get as much as ten times pensions more than the ex-Gurkhas.
</P>
<P>
When India became independent from British rule in 1947, the
Gurkhas, a part of the then Indian army, was divided with some
units remaining with India and others serving the British army
under the tripartite treaty. The treaty provides no discrimination
between British soldiers and Gurkha soldiers.
</P>
<P>
However, the British government when paying salaries and
pensions to Gurkhas cites the Indian army's pay scale,
maintaining that the 1947 treaty does not allow better facilities
for grouches in the British army than those in the Indian army.
</P>
<P>
The ex-Gurkha soldiers living in Nepal earlier had asked the
British government to meet their four-point demands, including
pensions for World War II veterans, equal pensions for British and
Gurkha soldiers, employment help for children of Gurkhas and
rights to live in Britain for retired Gurkha soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Some Nepali lawmakers also voiced their support for the
ex-Gurkha soldiers' demands, saying the issue is not only a
Gurkha's problem but one about national pride.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
