<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exchange Rate Change Not Needed: Thai Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Thai Central Bank Governor
Rerngchai Marakanond has said that changes to Thailand's foreign
exchange rate system were not needed.
</P>
<P>
He told a seminar on Friday that the country's economic
fundamentals are still strong, supported by the fiscal surplus for
nine consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Bhe Bank of Thailand governor added that short-term external
debt is still below the country's official foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
Early this month there was a heavy dumping of the baht in the
Hong Kong and Singapore swap markets in speculation of a baht
devaluation, triggered off by a poor Thai exports growth during
the first six months this year.
</P>
<P>
Rerngchai said at the seminar of bankers that the slowdown in
the Thai economy in the first half of this year was consistent
with the country's goal of maintaining macro-economic stability.
</P>
<P>
In his view, although the central bank recently revised its
forecast of the country's economic growth for this year from 8.3
percent to 7.8 percent, this did not signal a recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
