<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Subsidy Expected to Go </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- A continuous decline in the
monthly price index will drive out an inflation-beating interest
subsidy paid for long and medium-term savings deposits by the turn
of next year, according to the State Information Center.
</P>
<P>
An appropriately tight macro-economic control policy over the
past three years has enabled China to achieve an economic soft
landing it has envisaged, the center quoted figures released by
the State Statistical Bureau (SSB) as showing.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index was up 7.1 percent in the first half of
this year, much lower than the yearly target of 10 percent,
according to the SSB, which noted that the index for June and July
was as low as 5.9 and 5.8 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The center forecast the price index at seven percent for the
third quarter and 7-7.5 percent for the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the retail price index for the whole of 1996 is
expected to stand around 7.2 percent, the center said.
</P>
<P>
"Under this backdrop, the interest subsidy rate will continue
to drop significantly and down to nothing by the end of this year
or the beginning of next year," the center predicted.
</P>
<P>
China inaugurated the interest subsidy in 1988 to counter the
ravage of inflation, which soared to 21.7 percent in 1994. The
subsidy was suspended in 1991 and reintroduced in July 1993.
</P>
<P>
The subsidy rate, announced monthly by the People's Bank of
China, is calculated on the basis of a general retail price index
published by the SSB and is added to the normal interest rate for
savings deposits of three years and longer.
</P>
<P>
In response to declining price rises since last year, the
central bank suspended the subsidy for new deposits on April
1. The decision was not retrospective.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
