<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senators Call for Suspension of Peace Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine minority senators have
urged the government to suspend its schedule of signing the
Mindanao peace deal later this month, saying that most of the
people in southern Philippines are against the pact, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to senate minority leader Edgardo Angara, hearings by
senate subcommittees in four Mindanao cities since Thursday
indicated a strong opposition in the region against the
establishment of the Southern Philippines Council for Peace and
Development (SPCPD), which is provided in the unsigned peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Malacanang (the presidential palace) should not push it,
because the senate's initial public hearings in Mindanao have
convinced us more than ever that the (proposed) council will not
work. The government and the MNLF (MORO National Liberation
Front) should hammer out a modified peace formula," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged MNLF Chairman Nur Misuari to attend future senate
hearings, stressing that Misuari's face-to-face meeting with
senators is crucial to drafting a revised peace agreement that
could defuse the tension and spell genuine peace and development
in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
However, some senators have already started to soften their
opposition against the establishment of the SPCPD, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Christians in Mindanao have stepped up their protest
in the past few days as the government and the MNLF are reportedly
scheduled to sign the final peace pact on August 28 in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Despite warnings from President Fidel Ramos, the city council
of Zambo Friday announced that it would push through with its plan
to purchase 1,000 rifles to arm its citizens against Muslim
"atrocities" if the SPCPD is set up.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that Christians in some cities planned to
stage bigger protest rallies at the end of the month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
