<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands Rejects U.S. Sanction Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch government today
rejected the United States' imposition on third countries of its
unilateral laws punishing foreign companies doing business with
Cuba, Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
On August 5, U.S. President Bill Clinton signed another law
known as d'Amato act aimed at discouraging foreign investment in
Iran and Libya despite strong opposition from the allies to the
Helms-Burton act he signed earlier in March to enforce sanctions
against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Dutch government stressed that the
U.S. extra-territorial laws "overtly violate the multilateral
agreements on world trade and investment."
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the Netherlands is the world's seventh
biggest country in trade and sixth in international
investment. Furthermore, it is the third biggest foreign investor
in the United States, which is also the biggest investor in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Therefore the country's interests in trade and investment are
extremely vulnerable to these U.S. sanction laws, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
It announced that the Dutch government is actively
participating in preparing counter-retaliatory measures among the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the Netherlands also plans to develop its own laws to
protect its rights and interests, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
