<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Public Servants To Receive Salary Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 10 (Xinhua)-- All government servants will
receive a substantial salary increase with effect from January 1
next year, Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga announced
Friday, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The government decided on this measure after reviewing the
increasing cost of living, the president told a public rally on
Friday evening in Ratnapura town, over 100 kilometers from
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the private sector in Sri Lanka too will
be asked to consider this proposal by the government.
</P>
<P>
The government decided on a pay hike for public servants on a
recommendation made by the salaries commission, the reports quoted
the president as saying.
</P>
<P>
Members of the armed forces and police will be included in the
pay hike scheme, said the president, adding that the government
has already taken steps to increase the allowances of armed forces
and police personnel serving in the operational areas.
</P>
<P>
The Colombo Consumers' price index for the month of June this
year was 1970.8. This shows an increase of 81.3 index points or
4.3 percent compared to the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Annual average inflation on the basis of 12 months moving
average increased to 13 percent in June this year from 12.8
percent in the previous month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
