<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Federal Forum Fails to Make Headway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 9 (Xinhua) - A forum designed to strengthen
the Muslim-Croat federation has failed to yield expected results,
a leading Croat official said today.
</P>
<P>
Kresimir Zubak, who is president of the Muslim-Croat
federation, was commenting on Thursday's session of the forum,
which was also attended by U.S. envoy John Kornblum, international
peace coordinator Carl Bildt and Croatian Foreign Minister Mate
Granic.
</P>
<P>
Zubak said in a statement that Muslims and Croats initially
agreed at the meeting to sign two documents: a general declaration
obliging the Croats to abolish their state "Herzeg-Bosnia" and the
Muslim-led republic government to transfer certain powers to the
federation and a document specifying concrete steps and deadlines
for the implementation process.
</P>
<P>
According to Zubak, the Muslim side later denied "all that had
been agreed".
</P>
<P>
Zubak said that the Croats were "ready to transfer powers from
Herzeg-Bosnia to the Federation if the federal partner applied the
same process to the bodies of the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina
at the same time".
</P>
<P>
Toward the end of the forum session, Zubak said, the Muslim
side insisted that the declaration include a "condition that
Herzeg-Bosna be immediately abolished", which was rejected by the
Croats.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Croats caught the headlines around the world by
announcing that they would abolish their state. But few people
believe this promise will soon be carried out since there is still
deep mistrust between the Muslims and Croats, who reluctantly
formed the alliance under the pressure of the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
