<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Software Business Boosted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese personal computer
companies are expected to set up an association soon to promote
the development and application of domestically-made software.
</P>
<P>
To encourage growth of the country's software industry, China
will also start to decrease imports of foreign-made software,
today's China Daily quoted Yang Tianxing, director-general of the
Ministry of Electronics Industry, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, the China Software Industry Assn and five major
Chinese PC makers announced Friday the successful development of a
software pack for multi-media PCs with the cooperation of the US
firm Intel, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that the ministry has signed a full-scale technical
cooperative agreement with Intel for Chinese software development
as well as the popularization of China-made multi-media PCs in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The software pack, called Home CD, is contained on four compact
disks and published by the China Electronics Industry Publishing
House. It includes all of the current multi-media software, such
as programs for integrated installation, education, word
processing and dictionary, and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that the product will only be sold as an integral
part of China-made PCs -- Great Wall, Legend, Langchao, Tontru and
SeaStar.
</P>
<P>
Michael Bruck, general manager of Intel Technical Development
Co., Ltd, said that his company is focusing its technical aid to
China on large-scale integrated circuits, multi-media PCs,
enterprise computing, and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Liang Xiangfeng, president of the China Electronics Industry
Publishing House, said that Intel and other companies that took
part in developing the software have given the publishing house an
exclusive licence to their copyrights under an intellectual
property rights agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
