<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shell Snags Deal for Oil Prospecting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- China's onshore oil industry has
stepped up foreign cooperation in oil exploration and development
by letting the Anglo-Dutch oil giant Shell enter the Bohai Bay
Basin to search for oil.
</P>
<P>
The China National Petroleum Corp (CNPC) and the Shell
Exploration (China) Ltd signed a contract yesterday in Beijing for
exploration in the Qingshui Block, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The prospecting will be conducted at depths over 3,500 meters,
a depth never before plumbed in China. It is hoped the drilling
will uncover new, multiple kinds of reserves of oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
This contract represents the first foreign participation in
exploring deep underground. It is the industry's 30th foreign
cooperative oil contract. Shell will act as operator in the
563-square-kilometer block, shoulder risks and costs and share
reserves when they are discovered.
</P>
<P>
CNPC executives noted that the 30 contracts are diverse,
encompassing areas such as risk exploration, technical solutions,
and enhancement of oil recovery at old oil fields.
</P>
<P>
"The contrast, to be implemented at Liaohe, whose production
accounts for one-third of the country's total, is significant for
opening new horizons and quickening exploration," said Wu Yaowen,
CNPC's assistant president.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
