<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investments Drop Drastically in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Investments in projects approved
by the Philippine Board of Investments in the first semester this
year plummeted by 46 percent from the same period last year to
79.5 billion pesos (three billion U.S. dollars), the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista, who is
concurrently chairman of the Board of Investments, attributed the
drop to a smaller number of big-ticket projects.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of 1995, the board approved several
capital-intensive projects, including a petroleum refinery, major
telecommunications facilities, and petrochemical and cement
plants.
</P>
<P>
Bautista expressed confidence that the inflow of investments
would accelerate in the second half of the year, as projects
costing at least six billion U.S. dollars are expected to seek
approval of the board before yearend.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
