<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plant Quarantine to Be Tightened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese quarantine officers have
been asked to keep close watch over fruits and vegetables brought
into the country because some top dangerous pests may hide inside
them.
</P>
<P>
Mediterranean fruit flies and moths eating apple and coffee
bean have been discovered for several times from fruits brought by
foreigners at the Beijing Capital International Airport since
July, according to officials with the State Animal and Plant
Quarantine Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Those insects have been listed as the top dangerous pests in
China, the officials said, so keeping them out of the country is
vital to China's fruit and vegetable production.
</P>
<P>
The moth can completely destroyed fruits of apple, pear and
pitch, and coffee beans. The fruit flies can even cause death of
some 250 types of fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
The officials warned that the summer is especially key to
quarantine work because the hot and humid environment is good to
breeding of the pests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
