<HEADLINE> NZ, South Africa Sign Disarmament Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 10 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand has signed a
memorandum of cooperation with South Africa, which includes the
pursuit of a Southern Hemisphere nuclear-free zone.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed in Cape Town, South Africa, on Saturday
by visiting NZ Prime Minister Jim Bolger and South African
President Nelson Mandela, a local press report said today.
</P>
<P>
The document also covers the comprehensive nuclear test ban
treaty talks, and calls for the eradication of anti-personnel
landmines.
</P>
<P>
"We affirm the objective of a Southern Hemisphere free of
nuclear weapons," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Our governments will work together with other like-minded
countries with a view to developing increased cooperation between
existing or prospective nuclear weapon free zones, which, with the
addition of Antarctica, cover more than 50 percent of the earth's
land mass."  
</P>
</TEXT>
