<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chip Industry Shows Sluggishness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The world's semiconductor
industry's leading indicator fell in July for the first time in
three months, a sign that the industry may not be rebounding after
all.
</P>
<P>
But market analysts have questioned the validity of the
book-to-bill ratio, because it only covers North America and South
America, which constitute only one-third of the worldwide chip
market.
</P>
<P>
But the news still came as a blow to some chip stocks on Wall
Street, such as Micron Technology, LSI Logic, Texas Instruments,
and Motorola all went down. However, Intel bucked the trend in
active Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
The book-to-bill ratio, compiled by the Semiconductor Industry
Association, fell to a preliminary 0.85 for July, from a revised
0.88 in June, and significantly lower than the 0.95 analysts had
projected.
</P>
<P>
That means that for every 100 U.S. dollars for chips shipped,
chip companies received only 85 U.S. dollars in new orders.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts had expected the ratio to rise for the third
month in a row. Such a rise would have cemented a widespread
belief that the chip industry is emerging from a slump.
</P>
<P>
New orders for July were 2.81 billion U.S. dollars, 5 percent
below June's 2.96 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currently, computer memory chips make up about 30 percent of
the chip market. So the decline of chip orders indicated also a
slowdown in the computer industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Turn Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street turned
lower near the close today as a discouraging report on
semiconductor sales dampened enthusiasm over a tame inflation
report that sent interest rates lower in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 32.18 to 5,681.31.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with its volume totaling 325.15
million shares as against 334.56 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE's composite index fell 0.47 to 353.44, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 0.49 to 662.10.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 1.66 to 1,135.85, and the
American Stock Exchange's market value index fell 0.97 to 550.80.
</P>
<P>
Bonds rallied this morning after the Labor Department reported
that wholesale prices were unchanged in July, the latest in a
series of signals that inflation is not threatening a six-year
economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond slipped below 6.7
percent for the first time since early April, when inflation fears
were becoming rampant.
</P>
<P>
Despite the good news on inflation and interest rates, however,
the stock market was pulled down by Thursday evening's news that a
widely watched indicator of semiconductor industry performance
fell last month, reversing a gain in June that had revived hopes
for speedier growth of the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
