<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Has To Pay 42 Bln Dlrs for Eastward Expansion: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) might have to pay 42 billion U.S. dollars over
the next 10 to 15 years for its eastward expansion to include four
new members, according to a Pentagon-commissioned report today.
</P>
<P>
The study said that the estimated cost of adding Poland, the
Czech Republic, Slovakia and Hungary to the western military
alliance would be just 1 or 2 percent above NATO's current
spending levels. The U.S. share of that would be an estimated 400
million to 750 million U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
But the report said that NATO would be worth spending the money
considering the benefits the alliance's expansion will have for
both individual countries and European security as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The 42 billion U.S. dollars plan is based on a more modest
"Joint-Power Projection" that would keep most of the alliance's
troops and weapons in Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
Russia has repeatedly stated its strong opposition to any NATO
enlargement that would put either nuclear weapons or large numbers
of Western troops in the new member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960810.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Sanctions Committee Selects "Overseers" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
United Nations, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Iraq Sanctions
Committee of the U.N. Security Council decided today on the
selection of four independent experts to supervise Iraq's oil
sale.
</P>
<P>
The experts in international oil trade who will serve as
"overseers" at the U.N. headquarters are Arnstein Wigestrand of
Norway, Maurey G. Lorenz of the United States, Bernard Cullet of
France and Alexandre V. Kramar of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Should there be a need for a fifth overseer as work progresses,
Xie Changxian of China would be recommended by the secretariat for
the post, according to the sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
Tono Eitel, chairman of the committee, has forwarded the names
of the selected experts to the secretary-general for appointment.
</P>
<P>
The selection of the "overseers" is another step forward for
implementation of Resolution 986 adopted by the Security Council
in April 1995. Following the resolution, Iraq is allowed to export
oil worth 2 billion dollars over six months for import of food,
medicine and other necessities so as to alleviate the suffering
caused by the six-year-old economic sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
