<HEADLINE> US Official in Russia for Chemical Weapons Ban Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. top arms control
official is visiting Russia to discuss ways of speeding up the
ratification of a three-year-old global chemical weapons ban, his
office said today.
</P>
<P>
John Holum, director of the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency
(ACDA), went to Moscow Thursday for a meeting of a special joint
group set up last month to discuss chemical weapons, ACDA
spokeswoman Christie Dragan told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will include a trip to the city of Volgograd "to
address issues of chemical weapons production facilities," the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Russia signed, along with a number of
other countries, the Chemical Weapons Convention in Paris in
January 1993, but neither has ratified it. The convention, which
bans the production, stockpiling and use of poison gas, has not
yet come into effect because only 60 of 65 countries required have
ratified it so far.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the week, Holum urged the Republican-controlled
U.S. Congress to speed up the procedure for the ratification of
the convention.
</P>
<P>
He stressed he believed the U.S. Congress move would promote
the ratification of the Russian parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
